[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Intro"]
[Result "*"]

{ The Queen's Indian Defense is an opening that usually has been labeled as solid but it can also be a good choice to play for a win. This opening has the following moves: }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6
{ It is a perfect opening to combine with the Nimzo-Indian Defense if the white player plays 3. Nf3. The plan for the black pieces is: central control and fastest development. The f8-bishop will go to e7 or d6, and the b8 knight will develop by d7 most likely. The king will castle short in almost every line. About the central control, in the Queen’s Indian Defense @@StartBracket@@QID@@EndBracket@@ there are 3 different ways: ...d5, ...c5 or Ne4. ...Ne4 seems too passive because some minor pieces will be exchanged and the resulting position are too dry, and I think it is easier to play for white. About ...c5, it brings a lot of interesting and double-edged positions. I think that this kind of positions favor white more than black, especially if white can play the d5 sacrifice in good terms. Moreover, the AlphaZero-Stockfish match where AlphaZero destroyed the QID in numerous ways is not a good PR campaign. So this series will discuss the lines where the black player wants to control the center of the board mostly with d5. In this kind of positions black can control the central squares without too many risks while keeping good chances of victory. This opening has some topics that can be applied in the majority of the following cases: 1@@EndBracket@@ d5 will be played when the white player threatens to play either e4 or d5 in good conditions but not before. It is important to avoid white's expansion in the center but rushing ...d5 is also not ideal. The main reason is to keep the b7 bishop active, controlling e4 and not give away space to the enemy. 2@@EndBracket@@ The c-pawn will remain on the initial square as long as possible but if needed it can be pushed to c5 @@StartBracket@@or c6@@EndBracket@@. If this happens it is very likely that we have to play with hanging pawns. 3@@EndBracket@@ If white plays cxd5 there are two options: If there is a knight on c3 and/or a bishop on f4, we will recapture with the f6 knight. If these pieces are not on these squares we will take back with the e pawn. These guidelines are general ideas that are highly dependent of each situation but can be applied in most of the cases. In the complex final positions I will use arrows to show the main plans of the black player to continue the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.e3 with 5.Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too much troubles.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop is a concession. Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7 { Developing the light squared bishop to its natural square. } 5. Bd3
{ Intending to castle short as soon as possible. If white follows this move order, it is very likely that he wants to play O-O, b3, Bb2, Nc3 and Rc1, one way or the other. }
5... d5
{ Controlling e4, and allowing the dark squared bishop to develop comfortably. }
6. O-O { The most logical continuation, following white's basic plan. } 6...
Bd6
{ Since white is only developing without asking any difficult questions, black can place the bishop on d6, where it will be more active, eyeing h2 and controlling the e5-square. Now, both bishops are aiming to the enemy king. }
7. Nc3
{ White keeps developing, now on the queenside. Black can follow his main plan. }
7... O-O
{ Putting the king into safety, and activating the rook.  8.Nb5  , harassing the bishop, is not a problem, because it can be moved to  Be7  .  After ...a6, the knight has to go back to c3 and black can reposition the bishop again. }
8. b3 { Supporting the c4-pawn and giving the b2-square for the bishop. } 8...
Nbd7
{ With all minor pieces developed, black can start to think on the middlegame. It is better to develop the knight via d7, so it can move towards the kingside, supporting the e4-square.   9.Nb5  we just play  Be7  followed with a7-a6 on the next move to relocate the bishop on d6. }
9. Bb2 { Natural move taking into account the last move played by white. } 9...
a6
{ ...a6 is an useful move that we want to play because it secures the bishop on d6. It also helps to handle the queenside if white starts an expansion on this side of the board. }
10. Rc1
{ A logical move, placing the rook on a file that can be opened at any point with cxd5. }
10... Qe7
{ Only spot for the queen, but from this square it controls the queenside, so white can not expand easily. If white exchanges pawns on d5, the queen will firm up the center. Moreover, the rooks are now connected.  Black's main plans are placing a knight on e4, bolstering it with ...f5 and ...Ndf6 if possible, and only play ...c5 or ...dxc4 if it brings some benefit to its position.  The black rooks may remain on the 8th rank, either on c8 overprotecting the c7-square to free the dark squared bishop, or on the central files.  The position is mostly symmetrical but it has an important difference: black can open the h1-a8 diagonal at any point, while white can't do the same with the a1-h8 diagonal unless black plays ...c7-c5. }
