[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.e3 with 5.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too much troubles.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop is a concession. Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7 { Developing the light squared bishop to its natural square. } 5. Nc3
{ With this move order, we will probably reach the same positions as in the previous line with 5. Bd3. The only difference is that, in this move order, white's bishop can check us with Bb5+, which has its own ideas. }
5... d5
{ As said in the introduction chapter, we play ...d5 when white is threatening to expand on the center with e4 or d5. In that case, we play ...d7-d5 to avoid it. }
6. cxd5 { Going for the critical line without developing the f1-bishop. } 6...
exd5
{ In this case, we will take with the pawn because our dark squared bishop hasn't moved yet, so we can place it on d6 right away.  With this setting, ...exd5 reaches a nice structure for black. Moreover, the Bb5+ with the knight on d5 is slightly awkward. }
7. Bb5+
{ Moves like  7.Bd3  ,  7.Be2  ,  7.b3  or  7.Ne5  lead to the main lines, like the last line showed. With this move order, the only move that makes sense is  7.Bb5+  , which provokes  ...c6  . }
7... c6
{ The downside of this move is that it blocks the bishop on b7, which loses control over the e4-square, and white can open the center.  On the upside, black no longer needs to spend a tempo on ...a6 because the c6-pawn performs the same role of preventing Nb5. }
8. Bd3 { Now white has enough pieces controlling e4 to open the position. }
8... Bd6
{ We are allowed to play ...Bd6 directly, so we take our chance. ...Nbd7 is also possible, but white's plan is to open the center with e4, so we want to castle as soon as possible. }
9. O-O { For white it is also better to castle before opening the center. }
9... O-O
{ Same for black, it is better to evacuate the king to safety before e4 happens. }
10. e4
{ Only move that makes sense. If white delays it, black can fight for the e4-square with ...Re8 and ...Ne4, avoiding white's main idea of opening the center. }
10... dxe4
{ We cannot allow e4-e5. Black would lose a lot of space @@StartBracket@@white also threatens to fork the bishop and knight@@EndBracket@@.  Taking with the knight is also possible, but with this break @@StartBracket@@in this position and other alike@@EndBracket@@ we will usually take with the pawn first, so we keep the option on the next move to avoid exchanging minor pieces. }
11. Nxe4
{ The natural capture. White just opened the center, so he should prefer to keep the bishop pair. }
11... Nxe4
{ In this case, if black does not exchange knights he will remain passive. }
12. Bxe4 Nd7
{ 12...h6  is possible, but it is better to keep the king's cover untouched if possible.   White wants to play  13.Bg5  , developing the last minor piece and gaining a tempo on the queen. With this maneuver, black can block with  ...Nf6  , also ending development. }
13. Bg5 { The most natural move. } 13... Nf6
{ Self pinning the knight, but it will not last long. Black's idea is to play ...h6, ...Re8 and ...c5 at the right time.  Some pieces will be exchanged, but black will have an equal position with all pieces active @@StartBracket@@the bishop on b7 will be active after ...c5@@EndBracket@@. }
