[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.e3 with 5.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too much troubles.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop is a concession. Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7 { Developing the light squared bishop to its natural square. } 5. a3
{ It is an interesting move, with the idea to expand on the queenside as soon as possible. It is a very rare move, but it is the most venomous variation with 4. e3. }
5... d5
{ Black moves the d-pawn before the bishop, intending to play ...Bd6. Moves like 6. Nc3 or 6. Bd3 don't make sense because these are a waste of time regarding the main lines. }
6. b4
{ This has been played a very few times, but this is the main idea of white's previous move. White is trying to progress on the queenside before black can consolidate.  Right now, the main threat is 7. c5, which would cramp black's position. }
6... a5
{ Harassing white's structure immediately. This move has never been played, so it will come as a surprise for your opponent. }
7. b5
{ One of the main follow-ups, keeping the a8-rook passive, fixing the c7-pawn and ensuring white's space advantage. But it also has its drawbacks. }
7... Nbd7
{ The move 7. b5 has locked the queenside, but also makes the break c4-c5 almost impossible. Now black can think of castling long, where the black king will remain very safe. }
8. Bb2 { Natural developing move. } 8... Ne4
{ Black has less space to maneuver, so it is better to exchange some pieces. With 8...Ne4, black will exchange a pair of knights as soon as the b1-knight is developed. }
9. Nbd2
{ There is nothing better. If white tries to expell the knight with  9.Bd3  , black can play  ...Bd6  without any worries of white taking on  e4  . }
9... Nxd2
{ As said, we exchange the knights. In this kind of position, the best square for black's knights is clearly e4, but we only need one knight to occupy it.  With only three minor pieces on the board, the lack of space already feels released. }
10. Qxd2 { The most logical reaction. } 10... Bd6
{ Continuing the development. Also, it hides the black intentions of ...O-O-O, keeping both options open for now. The queen will be better placed on e7 after the bishop has been developed.    10...Qf6  trying to castle long would be a mistake, because the queen would be on the same diagonal as the b2-bishop, making  11.c5!  a very interesting approach. }
11. cxd5
{ Fixing the center, before black plays ...dxc4 opening the b7-bishop. Black could have played ...dxc4 before, but I think it is better to focus on development.  With the pawn on d5, the e4-square is ours to place a knight on it and attack the kingside. }
11... exd5
{ Every time that white takes on d5 we recapture with the e-pawn, either in this position or before/after.  We follow it with ...Qe7 and ...O-O-O, where the black king will be very safe on b8.  A kingside assault with the pawns is possible, while white can no longer do the same on the queenside. }
