[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Bg5
{ Developing the dark squared bishop before playing e3 and pinning the knight. It is more natural than 4. Bf4. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the light squared bishop is mandatory for black, so we focus on this before anything else. This move covers the e4-square. }
5. e3
{ A solid approach. White is trying to develop all his pieces before any critical action. With the c1-bishop outside the pawnchain, we need to be careful when we have to play ...d5 and when it is not necessary. }
5... Be7 { Breaking the pin and preparing ...O-O. } 6. Nc3
{ White is following the plan. } 6... O-O
{ If ...O-O-O is not an option, it is preferred to ...O-O as soon as possible. This way, black can also wait one more move to see white's approach, an act on the center according to it.  As said before, ...d5 is a very commital move with the white bishop on g5, so it is better to delay it. }
7. Bd3
{ White finishes his development, preparing to castle. White is now threatening e4. }
7... d5 { Now it is the time to take the center before white does it. } 8. cxd5
{ This is the most critical continuation, although it is only the second most played move.  The main ideas for white are to open the c-file to put pressure on c7 and to avoid black from opening the main diagonal at his will with ...dxc4. These ideas are recurrent in almost every line when black plays ...d5. }
8... Nxd5
{ Following the first rule of thumb, if the white knight is on c3 and the dark squared bishop is on g5, we recapture with the knight. After the exchange of dark squared bishops, e4 is not good because of ...Nf4! or ...Nxc3 followed by ...c5. }
9. Bxe7
{ White cannot avoid exchanging some pieces, especially the bishop. For white, it is better to exchange on e7, keeping the pawn structure intact. }
9... Qxe7
{ Taking backwards makes no sense. The knight on  d5  is active, and now the queen is too. After  9...Nxc3  , black is clearly worse:  10.Bxh7!  Kh8  11.bxc3  @@StartBracket@@after  10...Kxh7?  11.Qc2+  we can stop the clock@@EndBracket@@ with an extra pawn for white.   10.Nxd5  is not a concern, because black can take back with  Bxd5  . }
10. Rc1
{ Placing the rook on the open file, pressing c7 and overprotecting on c3, keeping the option of taking with the rook on c3. }
10... c5
{ White is well placed and has no weaknesses, so black needs to spice things up a little bit to avoid passivity. ...c5 attacks the white center before the king castles. }
11. dxc5
{ Keeping the pawnchain together. 11...cxd4 was awkward for white to meet, because g2 is not protected. }
11... Nd7
{ The white king is in the center, so we keep developing. White must accept this sacrifice, because he needs some compensation for the faster development of the black pieces. }
12. cxb6 { 12.Nxd5  is also possible, but the position will be very similar. }
12... axb6
{ After this sequence, black is a pawn down, but he has a better development. White will most likely return the pawn in order to castle.  Black can get back the pawn on a2, or attack the center with ...Nc5 and ...Rfd8 if white gets greedy keeping the extra pawn without castling his king. }
