[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Bf4
{ Similar to the London System, but the c-pawn is already on c4, making his pawn structure less compact. }
4... Bb7 { As always on move 4. } 5. e3
{ The most played move by far. After developing the bishop, white protects the center and prepares to develop the other bishop and castle. }
5... Bb4+
{ In this position we play slightly different. This check disturbs white's development, now that Bd2 is not an option.  The bishop on f4 is not pressing anything in black's camp @@StartBracket@@on g5, it was pinning the knight@@EndBracket@@, so we can get away with this. }
6. Nfd2
{ Counterintuitive, but it is the main line. None of the possible cover moves are bad, but in all of them @@StartBracket@@ Nfd2, Nc3 and Nbd2 @@EndBracket@@ white's position has some disadvantage.  This is why 4. Bf4 is not a very precise move, even if the resulting position remains balanced. }
6... O-O
{ A move like ...Ne4 does not bring any special gains for black, so he focuses on following his main plan: castle and center control. }
7. a3
{ White can delay this move, but eventually it must be played, so it is better for white to play it right now. If not, black can think about ...d5 and ...Bd6, or ...Ne4. }
7... Be7
{ Only possible retreat. Black does not want to exchange a bishop for a knight on d2 that has moved twice already, easing the task for white to finish his development. }
8. Nc3
{ Most logical move. g2 is hanging, so Bd3 might not be an option until the knight returns to f3 or black is forced to play ...d5 @@StartBracket@@taking on g2 would be dangerous for black, but this way white needs to think about it@@EndBracket@@.  With 8. Nc3, white threatens to push e4, so black must commit in the center. }
8... d5 { Our typical response, fighting for the e4-square directly. } 9. cxd5
{ Avoiding any issues with ...dxc4. It forces black to commit in the center. }
9... Nxd5
{ We can play ...Nxd5 because of the f4-bishop. This way, the center is not fixed, and the white king is still in the center of the board with the bishop still on f1. }
10. Nxd5
{ A move like  10.Bg3  would give black enough time to punch in the center, taking benefit of the potentially weak king on  e1  with moves like  ...c5  .  Therefore, taking on d5 is the most logical follow up. }
10... exd5
{ This position is similar to other lines of the QID, but the knight on d2 is badly placed. White will spend some time moving this knight to a useful square.  The bishop on f4 is also not the brightest piece on the board, standing alone without any assistance.  Black wants to play ...c5, controlling the center and taking advantage of his misplaced pieces. }
11. b4 { Stopping ...c5. } 11... c5
{ Or maybe not! Black opens the position to take profit of the bad placement of the king, even at the cost of a pawn if necessary. }
12. bxc5
{ White cannot allow black to place a protected passed pawn on c4, so taking is mandatory. Taking with the b-pawn makes more sense, as white will try to use the b-file for himself. }
12... bxc5
{ Black's plans are to relocate the bishop on b7  @@StartBracket@@now it is within reach of a Rb1 or Qb1@@EndBracket@@, either on a6 or c6, and to contest the diagonal to the bishop on f4 with ...Bd6.  The bishop will go to a6 to fight for the f1-a6 diagonal followed with ...Nxa6 @@StartBracket@@ 13. Qb1 avoids it, since after the exchanges on a6 there is ...Qb7! that wins a piece@@EndBracket@@ to recycle it via c7-e6, or else it can be developed on c6. }
