[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.Nc3 5.Bg5 with Bh4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3
{ A logical move, aiming at the center both on e4 and d5. } 4... Bb7
{ Still black's choice for good. } 5. Bg5
{ Other moves like  5.e3  transposes to lines that have been already analyzed. This is the only move that provides a different outcome.  With this move, white pins the f6-knight, making e4 and d5 back in the menu. }
5... Be7
{ Breaking the pin and developing the last piece on the kingside. After ...d5, black would be able to recapture with the knight. }
6. Qc2
{ 6.e3  is the move with more games in this position, but it would transpose to the main line with 4. Bg5, so in this case it is better to check other alternatives. Developing the queen, this move reinforce the threat of e4. }
6... h6
{ Forcing a decision before commiting in the center.  6...d5  is playable, but including ...h6 is a good idea, checking white's intentions with this bishop. }
7. Bh4
{ Keeping the bishop, still bothering the knight. Also holding on the bishop pair for now, although it is still not clear if this will play a major role. }
7... d5
{ After finishing the main development @@StartBracket@@bishops and g8-knight@@EndBracket@@, there is no more useful moves to make, so it is time to play ...d5.   7...O-O  is also possible, but it allows e4, and although it is not the end of the world, there is no need to give all this space to white for free. }
8. cxd5
{ This is a recurrent idea for white, but with the queen on c2, it makes even more sense since the queen is already aiming at c7. }
8... Nxd5
{ Once again, with the dark squared bishop outside the pawnchain and on the same diagonal of our bishop on e7, we take with the knight, keeping the center mobile and the b7-bishop in play. }
9. Bxe7
{ White cannot avoid exchanges, so Bxe7 is the most logical move. White does not want to trade the knights on d5 if that means that the bishop on b7 becomes active.  Also, it is better to force black to exchange on c3, so this knight would have moves 3 times already @@StartBracket@@ g8-f6-d5-c3@@EndBracket@@ only to be exchanged for the other knight. }
9... Qxe7
{ ...Nxe7 makes no sense, the knight on e7 has nothing to do, and it would need to move again to perform some role in the game.  This way, the queen is already on an useful square, allowing the rooks to connect and occupy the central files. }
10. Nxd5
{ White wants to play e4, so this exchange in the center allows white to do it with an extra tempo. After the direct ...d5, black has the intermediate move ...Nxc3, with the bishop on b7 aiming at the e4-pawn. }
10... Bxd5
{ There is no reason to block the bishop's diagonal with ...exd5. The only concern should be e4, but as we will see, it is not a problem. }
11. e4
{ The most logical follow up, the most played, and the least demanding.  White tries to dominate the center, but he cannot hold it, since he lacks development and the white king is still in the center of the board. }
11... Bb7
{ Going back makes more sense to place the bishop again on b7 since moves like ...c5 or ...Nc6 are the way to go and ...Bc6 would block both options. }
12. Bd3
{ Last piece into action. It also allows 13. O-O and overprotects the e4-pawn. }
12... O-O
{ Before starting the assault in the center of the board, it is better to remove the king from any danger.  The check with Qa4+ could be annoying in some lines, so it is better to avoid it. We also have the option to activate the rook via d8. }
13. O-O
{ White can delay O-O, but there is no improvement he can do to justify it, so it makes more sense to play it at the first attempt. }
13... Nc6
{ One of the few times that we develop the knight via c6 without moving the c7-pawn.  In this case ...Nb4 is a threat, exchanging the light squared bishop that is holding the center.  The pawn on d4 is weak  @@StartBracket@@the bishop on d3 blocks the d-file for the rooks, so the d4-pawn can not be protected@@EndBracket@@. }
14. Rac1
{ The d4-pawn can not be safe with 'normal-direct' means, so white piles up on the c-file, aiming to exchange the d4-pawn for the one on c7.  This move also avoids 14...Nb4 because now white can take on c7, and the bishop on b7 is hanging.  Black is ok after the knight move, but with the main line black is fighting for the initiative instead of settling for a position where he can remain passive with the central control for white. }
14... Rfd8
{ Increasing the pressure on d4. It is better to use this rook, since the a-rook might be used to secure the c7-pawn in some cases. }
15. Qa4 { White keeps protecting the central pawn. } 15... Qd6
{ And black keeps attacking it. Black's ideas are to remove the central pawn, even if it means to exchange it for the pawn on c7.  The ending after mass exchanges should be slightly better for black, although it is holdable for white. }
