[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.Nc3 5.Bg5 with Bxf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3
{ A logical move, aiming at the center both on e4 and d5. } 4... Bb7
{ Still black's choice for good. } 5. Bg5
{ Other moves like  5.e3  transposes to lines that have been already analyzed. This is the only move that provides a different outcome.  With this move, white pins the f6-knight, making e4 and d5 back in the menu. }
5... Be7
{ Breaking the pin and developing the last piece on the kingside. After ...d5, black would be able to recapture with the knight. }
6. Qc2
{ 6.e3  is the move with more games in this position, but it would transpose to the main line with 4. Bg5, so in this case it is better to check other alternatives. Developing the queen, this move reinforce the threat of e4. }
6... h6
{ Forcing a decision before commiting in the center.  6...d5  is playable, but including ...h6 is a good idea, checking white's intentions with this bishop. }
7. Bxf6
{ Now white can sieze the center, and this will be one of the few occasions where we will allow it.  White has moved the c1-bishop twice, and the queen on c2 no longer has a plan. Therefore black can take advantage of these 'wasted moves' to attack the center. }
7... Bxf6
{ Taking with the pawn makes no sense, this is not a Sicilian Defense. } 8. e4
{ The main try. Other moves make no sense after commiting to Bxf6.  White has the central control, and black can not challenge it immediately, so white has to take his chance. }
8... d6
{ Following the main developing plan. Delaying the short castle makes sense, since white can choose between O-O and O-O-O. We will play ...O-O either way, but it is recommended to hinder the advance e4-e5.  It also makes it possible for black to close the center if needed with ...e6-e5, although first black needs to think what to do with the f6-bishop @@StartBracket@@after ...e6-e5 it will be very passive@@EndBracket@@. }
9. O-O-O
{ The most risky approach for both players, but also the funniest. We reach an opposite side castling, where usually the first player to strike is the one who wins the game. In this case, we are well prepared to meet this. }
9... Nd7
{ Developing the last minor piece with the intention of playing ...e5 or ...c5 at the right moment. }
10. h4
{ Natural move, going for the black kingside swiftly. Black's king is still on the center, but ...O-O-O is not an option because black has no space and he will be slowly crushed by the central pawns. }
10... O-O
{ There are no alternatives. Black can no longer make any other waiting move to improve his position, so he finally guards the monarch on the kingside. }
11. g4
{ A very logical follow up, but inaccurate. If white tries to attack our king right away, he is creating more problems for himself than to black. }
11... g6
{ If white keeps pushing his kingside pawns, we can close the position @@StartBracket@@for instance  12.h5  g5!  @@EndBracket@@. Black first has to focus on stopping the threats on his king before acting on the queenside. }
12. Qd2
{ A very logical move, attacking the h6-pawn, supporting the g4-g5 push and taking control of the d-file in the case white wants to push e4-e5 or c4-c5. }
12... Bg7
{ Protecting the weak pawn, removing the bishop from being attacked after g4-g5. }
13. d5 { Commiting in the center, waiting for black to reveal his intentions. }
13... c5
{ Position remains balanced, but white should be very careful. Black has fixed the c4-pawn, which means that ...b5 will open some files on the queenside.  ...Rc8/Rb8 and the maneuver ...Nb6-Na4, pressing on b2 with the g7-bishop are very strong threats.  On the kingside, black no longer needs to do any more preparation, so he should stay as quiet as possible. }
