[Black "4.a3 with Qa4+"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3
{ The second move most played in this position. This covers the b4-square, so the c3-knight cannot be pinned. Now 5. d5 for white is possible, so black must prevent that. }
4... Bb7
{ Again the same fourth move for black, placing the bishop on the right square and preventing d5. }
5. Nc3
{ ...Bb4 is no longer an option, so the knight comes to c3 without any hesitation. This is the most logical move, other moves @@StartBracket@@like 5. e3@@EndBracket@@ transposes to other main lines. 6. d5 is again a threat. }
5... d5
{ White wants to play d5, so we need to stop it. In this case, as ...Bb4 is not an option, the move for black has to be ...d5 again. In this position white has many options to carry out the game towards calmer or more stormy fields. }
6. Qa4+
{ According to computer, this is the best move, but very few games feature this position.  White's idea with this check is to disturb black's development, forcing to play some awkward move black does not want to play. For instance:  - ...Qd7: taking the square from the knight.  - ...c6: clogging the bishop.  - being annoying pinning some piece.  If needed, the queen can always come back to c2. }
6... Nbd7
{ This is the lesser evil, the knight will remain pinned for some moves, but the harmony of black's pieces has not been harmed.  After short castling, the knight will be released, so black must focus on getting the king out of the way. }
7. cxd5
{ With the queen on a4, ...dxc4 could gain some tempi in some lines because after Bxc4 a move like ...a6 would threaten a fork on b5.  So white exchanges on d5 at the first attempt, avoiding any worries and achieving the structure he wanted in the first place. }
7... Nxd5 { The white knight is on c3, so we can recapture with the knight. }
8. Nxd5
{ White wants to take profit of the c-file, so he cannot wait for black to exchange the knights on c3. }
8... Bxd5
{ Taking with the pawn is an inaccuracy, because the light squared bishop would be too passive. Thus we capture with the bishop, placing it on a very nice square. White cannot play e4, so there is nothing to be worried about.  This also allows black to finish development in a more comfortable manner, with ...c5 being more attractive as there is no option of having to deal with an isolated queen pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@ or hanging pawns on d5 and c5. }
9. Bg5
{ White has a lot of options on this move, but this looks very natural activating the last piece on the queenside and forcing a reaction from black, since it hits the queen.  It also has an idea that will be shown in the following moves. }
9... Be7 { Natural response, developing the bishop. } 10. Bxe7
{ White has nothing better, but that was his main intention on the last move. }
10... Qxe7 { Again a natural move, not too much to add here. } 11. Rc1
{ White's idea behind the bishop development via g5. After the queen has left the d8-square, the c7-pawn is hanging, so white develops another piece attacking the c7-pawn, hoping that black has to lose some time protecting it. }
11... O-O
{ Surprise! Black does not need to protect the pawn as he can play for the initiative.  White's king is still in the center of the board, and it requires two extra moves to find safety, so the pawn on c7 is not a problem.   In fact, after  12.Rxc7  Rfc8!  , white is in trouble, since black is not a pawn down, black is an open file up! For instance  13.Rxd7  Qe8!  and we are winning an exchange.   White can keep developing the kingside, but in that case black has a very easy play with ...c5 and activating the rooks, even exchanging the bishop on f3 to ruin white's castle. }
