[Black "4.a3 with Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3
{ The second move most played in this position. This covers the b4-square, so the c3-knight cannot be pinned. Now 5. d5 for white is possible, so black must prevent that. }
4... Bb7
{ Again the same fourth move for black, placing the bishop on the right square and preventing d5. }
5. Nc3
{ ...Bb4 is no longer an option, so the knight comes to c3 without any hesitation. This is the most logical move, other moves @@StartBracket@@like 5. e3@@EndBracket@@ transposes to other main lines. 6. d5 is again a threat. }
5... d5
{ White wants to play d5, so we need to stop it. In this case, as ...Bb4 is not an option, the move for black has to be ...d5 again. In this position white has many options to carry out the game towards calmer or more stormy fields. }
6. Bg5
{ The second move most played in this position. Pinning the knight, if black does nothing white will take on d5, and the recapture with either the pawn or the bishop is not ideal. }
6... Be7
{ So black has to break the pin, developing the last piece on the kingside and preparing for castle.  Now white can take on f6 and oblige black to take on d5 with the pawn, but in this case black would have the bishop pair to compensate it.  As a rule of thumb, if black can get the bishop pair in exchange for taking on d5 with the pawn, we are not too bothered about it, because both players have made concessions. }
7. e3
{ The main line. Very logical; after moving the c1-bishop 7. e3 makes a lot of sense, reinforcing the center and allowing the f1-bishop to move aside to castle. }
7... O-O
{ Black achieves nothing from delaying short castling, so this is a good moment to do so.  White cannot make much progress with this tempo, and we can wait to see how white wants to follow up his previous play. }
8. Rc1
{ Most common move, delaying moving the f1-bishop preventing black to win a tempo with ...dxc4. Now, the rook has been activated and is aiming at c7.   8.cxd5  is also an option, but white can wait for it. }
8... Nbd7
{ Developing the last minor piece. Now, white has to decide if he wants to take on d5 or if he wants to develop the bishop at the expense of losing a tempo after ...dxc4. }
9. cxd5
{ Not allowing black to take on c4 with tempo. Also forcing black to take with the pawn in this move order. }
9... exd5
{ We take with the pawn because c7 is weak.   After  9...Nxd5  10.Bxe7  , black has to choose to either lose the c7-pawn for no compensation or retreating the knight to  e7  , where black would need to spend another tempo to place this knight on a good spot. }
10. Bd3
{ Preparing O-O and placing the bishop on his best square, pressing on e4 and aiming at black's kingside. }
10... Ne4
{ Black had to take on d5 with the pawn, which mean that the e4-square is for black for the taking.  The knight on e4 is placed on his best square and the bishop on b7, although it is hitting his own pawn, is also indirectly sustaining the e4-knight.  The f6-square is clear for the other knight to join the party on e4. The only good @@StartBracket@@great!@@EndBracket@@ square for a knight in black's position is e4, so black can exchange one knight and still keep his stand in the center.  White needs to react to this, as the bishop on g5 is currently hanging. }
11. Bf4
{ White can also take on e7, but in a way it seems that he is helping black to finish development after ...Qxe7. So he keeps the bishops on the board increasing the pressure on c7. }
11... c5
{ Black needs to get rid of his weakness on c7 before it is too late. After ...c5, black gets rid of a problem while attacking the center and potentially seizing some space on the queenside.  The main idea for black right now is to take on c3 and move the c-pawn one more square forward. }
12. dxc5
{ Critical move, although it has never been played and has some flaws.  White tries to leave black with hanging pawns, maneuvering around them and taking some advantage from it, but black is well prepared to deal with this and even could be easily on top. }
12... Nxc3
{ This capture is awkward to meet for white. Both has its issues, but the main response is taking with the rook. }
13. Rxc3
{ White is exposing the rook on c3, which can be attacked with the bishop on f6, but taking with the pawn worsens white's pawn structure too much.  White needs to be precise. }
13... bxc5
{ Now black recaptures on c5. Black is left with hanging pawns, but the bishop on d3 and specially the rook on c3 are misplaced, so black can improve his position at the expense of these two pieces. }
14. O-O
{ White's king takes shelter, waiting for black to decide how to strike in the center. By transposition, we reached a position that had been played before. }
14... c4
{ Normally it is not good to decide so quickly when you have hanging pawns, but in this case black can take advantage of the rook on c3 to buy time.  Black's main moves are ...Bf6 and ...Nc5. Black's pieces are so active and white's pieces for the next few moves will be dancing around avoiding death.  The position is still balanced according to the engine, but white is walking a tightrope while black has all the fun. }
