1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3
{ The second move most played in this position. This covers the b4-square, so the c3-knight cannot be pinned. Now 5. d5 for white is possible, so black must prevent that. }
4... Bb7
{ Again the same fourth move for black, placing the bishop on the right square and preventing d5. }
5. Nc3
{ ...Bb4 is no longer an option, so the knight comes to c3 without any hesitation. This is the most logical move, other moves @@StartBracket@@like 5. e3@@EndBracket@@ transposes to other main lines. 6. d5 is again a threat. }
5... d5
{ White wants to play d5, so we need to stop it. In this case, as ...Bb4 is not an option, the move for black has to be ...d5 again. In this position white has many options to carry out the game towards calmer or more stormy fields. }
6. cxd5
{ The most played, in some cases ends up transposing to previous lines. } 6...
Nxd5
{ There is no bishop outside the pawnchain for white, but as the e-pawn is still untouched, black won't be able to play ...Bd6 before white develops his dark squared bishop to either f4 or g5.  So black wins nothing of taking on d5 with the pawn. Black should take with the knight, keeping consistency with previous occasions, although in this particular case taking with the pawn is also good due to white 'wasting' a tempo on a3. }
7. e3
{ This move blocks the c1-bishop and is not so logical, but the other natural moves at this point transposes to other main lines that have been already analyzed.  So this structure is the one that remains to be discussed. This is similar to the lines with 4. e3, where black was able to achieve what we can call 'the perfect position'  (bishop on d6 and ...Ne4 looming)  .  But, in this case, white's position is better because black already commited in the center with ...Nxd5 and the bishop on d6 could be hit by the e-pawn in the future. }
7... Be7
{ As d6 is not an option for the bishop, black develops it on the most common square. }
8. Bb5+
{ The light squared bishop hasn't moved yet, so it forces ...c6 before landing on d3, trying to get the black to compromise on his position with a move he does not want to make. }
8... c6
{ Selfpinning or blocking the c-pawn is not great, so black blocks with ..c6 forcing the bishop to move again. In the near future black will play ...c6-c5, so this issue will not last long. }
9. Bd3 { After doing the job, the bishop returns to his natural position. }
9... Nxc3
{ ...Nxc3, ...O-O and ...c5 can be played in several move orders, but starting with ...Nxc3 gives fewer alternatives to white. Black wants to castle short and play ...c5 to release his position, heading to an equal middlegame. }
10. bxc3
{ White gets a healthy structure in the center, with his spearhead on d4 being reinforced with two pawns. If white can play e4 in good conditions, he will be on top. }
10... O-O
{ Sheltering the king before hitting the center, avoiding problems with Bb5+ back. }
11. O-O
{ 11.e4  is also possible but it will transpose to the main line. White has to remove the king from the center anyway, so it makes sense to do it right away. }
11... c5
{ Black cannot remain inactive. White is making progress in the center, so black strikes immediately with this typical pawn break. }
12. e4
{ White seizes the center. For now black has lost the central control, but he will strike back shortly. }
12... Qc7
{ Supporting the c-pawn, taking the c-file and most importantly preventing white to develop his last minor piece to his ideal square on f4.  Now white has some difficulties to find an active spot for the  c1-bishop and as a consequence his rooks still can not join the action properly. }
13. Qe2
{ Removing the queen from the first rank, delaying the bishop development for now. Be3 is a possibility, but in that case the e4-pawn would be weaker. }
13... Rd8 { Attacking the center. } 14. Bb2
{ The dark squared bishop is blocked by his own pawns, but it can not move to any good square for now, so white moves it out of the way so his rooks can be activated. }
14... Nd7
{ Developing the last piece and connecting the rooks. Black is ready to strike to regain control of the game. }
15. Rad1
{ A logical move. It makes sense to start with this rook move so the bishop can go back to c1 if needed without disrupting the rooks connection. }
15... c4
{ Novelty to shake up the position a little bit. After ...Bxc4 black can take on e4 due to the hanging bishop on c4 after Qxe4.  It is better to remove the bishop to c2 or b1, and on that case black can gain a lot of space on the queenside, where we already have more pieces involved. White will try an assault on the kingside, but the knight on d7 could defend it from f8 easily.  Meanwhile white has fewer resources to counter black's progress on the queenside, unless white starts removing his pieves from the kingside to the queenside. }
