1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3
{ The best, and the move that is played the most by far. The bishop will be developed by g2, which allows a quick short castling, solving white's problems with the king on many of the lines already seen. }
4... Bb7
{ Now that white will counter the long diagonal directly, this move makes even more sense than in previous occasions. }
5. Bg2
{ The move that has been played the most by far, allowing white to castle and placing the bishop on its natural square. }
5... Be7
{ ...d5 is premature since there is no white knight on c3 neither the c1-bishop has been developed. There is no other sensible move than this one, also allowing black to castle on the next move. }
6. O-O
{ This move is the most logical not only for king's safety, but because now the g2-bishop is protected and white can think on moving the f3-knight without worrying about the g2-bishop. }
6... O-O
{ Like in the last move, ...d5 is still inaccurate. Black also castles before commiting in the center. }
7. Re1
{ Interesting move, delaying Nc3 for the moment. It is not a principal move, but it can be hard to deal with with black. }
7... d5
{ White is not threatening to play e4 but black has no other waiting move, so he must compromise in the center.  Again ...d5 is our choice although white has not developed neither the c1-bishop or the b1-knight, but black has no good alternatives. }
8. cxd5
{ Now white takes on d5 on his best conditions, before developing the queenside's knight and bishop. }
8... exd5
{ Black cannot take with a piece, since after  7...Nxd5  8.e4  white takes the center and after  7...Bxd5  8.Nc3  black is not happy.   So black is forced to take with the pawn in a position where he has already commited his dark squared bishop to e7. }
9. Nc3
{ Now white finally develops the knight. White's position in the center is the best he can get in this opening, but white has some drawbacks.  The e1-rook seems out of place as e4 cannot be pushed so it is not clear what it is doing on e1. }
9... Nbd7
{ Developing the last minor piece, aiming to reinforce the other knight on e4. }
10. Bf4
{ Since the f6-knight would not be pinned, it makes more sense to develop the bishop to f4, targeting the weakness on c7. }
10... Ne4 { Black is ready to move forward. } 11. Rc1
{ Threatening c7 indirectly and overprotecting the c3-knight. } 11... Nxc3
{ As in similar positions, black only needs one knight on e4, so he confidently exchanges one pair of knight even if black's knight has moved three times.  White was also threatening to remove the c3-knight to target c7 with two pieces, so the exchange makes even more sense. }
12. bxc3
{ Both captures are possible. Taking with the pawn, white keeps his pawn structure intact reinforcing the center with an extra pawn.  A timely c4 is also looming in the position as the bishop on b7 is not protected. }
12... Re8
{ Developing the rook and leaving the f8-square for the bishop, fighting for the e4-square.  Black's ideas are to remove the bishop from the e7-square where currently it is doing nothing, freeing the e-file for the rook and in some cases the f6-square for the queen.  ...c5 is an obvious break black wants to play in a lot of cases and this position is not an exception. With the white pawn on c3, black should not worry about hanging pawns after ...c5. }
