{ The best, and the move that is played the most by far. The bishop will be developed by g2, which allows a quick short castling, solving white's problems with the king on many of the lines already seen. }
4... Bb7
{ Now that white will counter the long diagonal directly, this move makes even more sense than in previous occasions. }
5. Bg2
{ The move that has been played the most by far, allowing white to castle and placing the bishop on its natural square. }
5... Be7
{ ...d5 is premature since there is no white knight on c3 neither the c1-bishop has been developed. There is no other sensible move than this one, also allowing black to castle on the next move. }
6. O-O
{ This move is the most logical not only for king's safety, but because now the g2-bishop is protected and white can think on moving the f3-knight without worrying about the g2-bishop. }
6... O-O
{ Like in the last move, ...d5 is still inaccurate. Black also castles before commiting in the center. }
7. d5
{ This is the moment when it makes the most sense to play d5, after castling. White gives up a pawn to uncoordinate black's pieces.  To regain control of the position, black most likely will have to return the pawn. The bishop on g2 will dominate the diagonal and white pieces are heading to the kingside. }
7... exd5
{ Black should take the pawn so he has some compensation for the activity of white's pieces. This sacrifice is considered to give nothing to white at the top level, but still black needs to know what he is doing. }
8. Nh4
{ The main idea. White is activating the g2-bishop and rerouting the knight towards the f5-square, where it attacks g7, our dark squared bishop and also the d6-square in some lines. }
8... c6
{ Black cannot let white take on d5 and control the center so he must bolster it with the c-pawn.  This also clears the c7-square for the knights from where they could protect the d5-square. }
9. cxd5
{ With the last move black closed the diagonal so ...dxc4 was threatened. White has to take on d5 to avoid that. }
9... Nxd5
{ Black must take with the knight to avoid the doubled pawns.  If white wants to cripple black's structure he has to exchange his precious bishop, and he does not want to do that. The knight will maneuver to c7 and maybe e6. }
10. Nf5
{ Placing the knight on its ideal square, hitting several important points in black's territory. }
10... Nc7
{ The best way to break free is to play ...d5, so the knight must first be removed from this square. On c7 it may seem strange, but from this square it can reach e6 or e8 @@StartBracket@@defending g7@@EndBracket@@ and leaves the f6-square for the bishop.   11.Nxe7  is not a problem because white would exchange one of his two active pieces and black would remain a pawn up.   The same could be said about  11.Nd6  ; after  11...Bxd6  and  12.Qxd6  Nb5  black can release himself advancing the d-pawn. }
11. e4
{ Main move for white, hindering the ...d5 push for black. Also leaving the way clear for the queen to join the kingside assault. }
11... d5
{ This is the moment to strike in the center. Black will most likely lose the extra pawn, but his pieces will be activated. }
12. Nc3
{ For now white does not need to rush to get back the pawn.  Instead white keeps developing, adding the pieces from the queenside while black queenside is still in a piece jam. }
12... Bf6
{ It is not good to take on e4, since in that case black's pieces would remain piled up on the queenside, while the main action is happening on the kingside.  It is better to replace the bishop, avoiding the exchange now that Nd6 is no longer possible and controlling the e5-push for white and the ...d4 push for black. }
13. exd5
{ Recovering the pawn before it is too late, resigning himself to an ending. }
13... Nxd5
{ Exchanging some passive pieces before leaving the d5-pawn isolated and doomed. After these exchanges, black's position is solid and has no problems with development.  White cannot continue the attack without risking ending up in an ending a pawn down. }
