[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.g3 with Nc3 & cxd5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3
{ The best, and the move that is played the most by far. The bishop will be developed by g2, which allows a quick short castling, solving white's problems with the king on many of the lines already seen. }
4... Bb7
{ Now that white will counter the long diagonal directly, this move makes even more sense than in previous occasions. }
5. Bg2
{ The move that has been played the most by far, allowing white to castle and placing the bishop on its natural square. }
5... Be7
{ ...d5 is premature since there is no white knight on c3 neither the c1-bishop has been developed. There is no other sensible move than this one, also allowing black to castle on the next move. }
6. O-O
{ This move is the most logical not only for king's safety, but because now the g2-bishop is protected and white can think on moving the f3-knight without worrying about the g2-bishop. }
6... O-O
{ Like in the last move, ...d5 is still inaccurate. Black also castles before commiting in the center. }
7. Nc3
{ White keeps developing his pieces. This move reinforces the center of the board. e4 is still not possible, but d5 is a major threat. }
7... d5
{ Black must react in the center. As always in these cases, black should occupy the center with his own pawns, strengthening his central position on the squares d5 and e4.    7...Ne4  is also possible but it is not my recommendation. It feels more passive and it leads towards a risk-free position for white. }
8. cxd5
{ Second most played in this position. Defining the center at the first attempt and not worrying about ...dxc4 possibilities. }
8... Nxd5
{ There is a knight on c3, so we can @@StartBracket@@and must!@@EndBracket@@ recapture with the knight. }
9. Re1 { Intending e4. Black should stop it. } 9... Nxc3
{ First we need to exchange the d5-knight which is interfering with the other black pieces for acting in the center. }
10. bxc3
{ Only move. White is now aiming at the unprotected b7-bishop so black needs to be aware of the knight's discoveries. }
10... Be4
{ Stopping e4 for good. Now white will have to exchange his g2-bishop if he wants to fight for the center. }
11. Ne5
{ Resigning himself to exchange his precious g2-bishop, white activates his knight hoping to disrupt black's remaining pieces obstructing his queenside development. }
11... Bxg2 { Other movements lose ground, which is an unnecessary concession. }
12. Kxg2
{ White is hitting the c6-square which seems to delay the b8-knight's play. After  12...Nd7  white can exchange our bishop with  13.Nc6  . }
12... Nc6
{ A nice tactical motif since ...Qd5+ gets the piece back. With this move, white cannot control the center and black can fully develop his pieces without any headache. }
13. Nxc6
{ Retreating the knight is an alternative, but first we must check the resulting position after taking the bait. }
13... Qd5+
{ White can seize the center with e4, but with so many minor pieces having left the board black has no space problems.  Black's main ideas are to place both rooks in the d-file attacking the center, locate his bishop on the long diagonal and push the c-pawn to finally crack white's central pawns. }
