[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.g3 with Nc3 & Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3
{ The best, and the move that is played the most by far. The bishop will be developed by g2, which allows a quick short castling, solving white's problems with the king on many of the lines already seen. }
4... Bb7
{ Now that white will counter the long diagonal directly, this move makes even more sense than in previous occasions. }
5. Bg2
{ The move that has been played the most by far, allowing white to castle and placing the bishop on its natural square. }
5... Be7
{ ...d5 is premature since there is no white knight on c3 neither the c1-bishop has been developed. There is no other sensible move than this one, also allowing black to castle on the next move. }
6. O-O
{ This move is the most logical not only for king's safety, but because now the g2-bishop is protected and white can think on moving the f3-knight without worrying about the g2-bishop. }
6... O-O
{ Like in the last move, ...d5 is still inaccurate. Black also castles before commiting in the center. }
7. Nc3
{ White keeps developing his pieces. This move reinforces the center of the board. e4 is still not possible, but d5 is a major threat. }
7... d5
{ Black must react in the center. As always in these cases, black should occupy the center with his own pawns, strengthening his central position on the squares d5 and e4.    7...Ne4  is also possible but it is not my recommendation. It feels more passive and it leads towards a risk-free position for white. }
8. Bf4
{ This alternative move does not demand great knowledge to get a good position with black. It makes more sense to play this move after exchanging on d5. }
8... dxc4
{ The best, avoiding cxd5 and simplifying white's options. Black rarely takes this pawn so early in this course. However, in this case black is threatening to consolidate his extra pawn with the a6-b5 chain. }
9. Qa4
{ Only move to consider, regaining the pawn as soon as possible. The pawn is doomed as black cannot hold on to the extra pawn without making some positional concessions. }
9... Nd5
{ But there is no need to do it. Black wants the bishop pair to have some advantage in the ensuing middlegame. Of course taking the knight is not an option as it consolidates black's extra pawn. }
10. Qxc4
{ White cannot save the bishop as ...Nxc3 would allow black to keep his extra pawn after ...Bd5.   10.Bd2  Nxc3  11.bxc3  Bd5  and black keeps the extra pawn.  Therefore white recaptures the pawn now, avoiding unnecessary problems. }
10... Nxf4
{ Black exchanges the knight for the bishop. Now black does not have to worry for the c7-pawn  @@StartBracket@@at least for now@@EndBracket@@ and he removed one of his knights which gives some breathing room for the other pieces. }
11. gxf4
{ On the bright side for white, he has more presence in the center of the board, especially on the e5-square. }
11... Bd6
{ Improving the bishop and pressing the new doubled pawn, leaving the e7-square for other pieces which can make a better use of it. }
12. Rfd1
{ With the direct  12.Ne5  , we can exchange the bishops  ...Bxg2  13.Kxg2  and play  ...Qh4  disturbing white's king so it is more precise to start with this improving move.  Now white has added the menace of pushing d5. }
12... Nc6
{ Uncommonly, in this position the knight has more options on c6 than on d7. It can harass the queen from a5 or transfer itself to the kingside via e7.   After  12...Nd7  the maneuver  13.Ne5  and Nc6 next would be an issue. The f4-pawn is poisoned because of d5! }
13. Ne5 { Attacking the pinned knight and activating the bishop. } 13... Na5
{ Only move.  Attacking the queen as black has managed to exchange the dangerous g2-bishop without major concessions. On the right moment black should expell the e5-knight with ...f6 and reroute his knight to the kingside via c6-e7. }
