[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.g3 with Ne5 & cxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3
{ The best, and the move that is played the most by far. The bishop will be developed by g2, which allows a quick short castling, solving white's problems with the king on many of the lines already seen. }
4... Bb7
{ Now that white will counter the long diagonal directly, this move makes even more sense than in previous occasions. }
5. Bg2
{ The move that has been played the most by far, allowing white to castle and placing the bishop on its natural square. }
5... Be7
{ ...d5 is premature since there is no white knight on c3 neither the c1-bishop has been developed. There is no other sensible move than this one, also allowing black to castle on the next move. }
6. O-O
{ This move is the most logical not only for king's safety, but because now the g2-bishop is protected and white can think on moving the f3-knight without worrying about the g2-bishop. }
6... O-O
{ Like in the last move, ...d5 is still inaccurate. Black also castles before commiting in the center. }
7. Nc3
{ White keeps developing his pieces. This move reinforces the center of the board. e4 is still not possible, but d5 is a major threat. }
7... d5
{ Black must react in the center. As always in these cases, black should occupy the center with his own pawns, strengthening his central position on the squares d5 and e4. }
8. Ne5
{ The main move, seeking the initiative and freeing the main diagonal for the g2-bishop, avoiding the positions where black freed himself with ...dxc4 and waiting to develop the c1-bishop. }
8... Nbd7
{ Developing the last minor piece. This position is one of the most played in this line and also a good example of how black has to develop.  The f6-knight is ready to jump to e4 while the d7-knight will replace its fellow on f6. The bishops on e7 and b7 are ready to join the action. }
9. cxd5
{ The second main move in this position where white defines the center.  White has a good score in this position but that is because most players made the wrong recapture in the next move. }
9... Nxd5
{ More than half of the games that had reached this position @@StartBracket@@around 250@@EndBracket@@ follow it with  9...exd5?  which is a mistake.  After  10.Qa4  white accomplished a dream position  with Nc6 looming and a very active position while black cannot activate his pieces properly.   But taking with the knight on d5 is the correct move as there is a white knight on c3 not allowing white to control the position without compensation. }
10. Nxd5
{ The most logical move. We have already seen positions like this where white does not wish us to take on c3, simplifying the position in our favor. }
10... exd5
{ With the knight on e5, taking with the bishop is usually not a good idea. After the diagonal has been opened, Nc6 is a possibility, and one that gives the bishop pair to white in a semi-open position that black will not enjoy.   10...Bxd5  11.Nc6  . }
11. Nd3
{ Saving the knight, and placing it on a very good square. On d3 it controls c5 and e5, can move to f4 if necessary and does not block the bishop on g2.  Also, it allows a queenside expansion with b4. The engine slightly prefers 11. Bf4, but I think this is a better move at least in a practical sense. }
11... Re8
{ Eyeing the e4-square and leaving the f8-square for the bishop or the knight. }
12. b4
{ Moving the action to the queenside. If white can play b5 in good terms, he could be much better because black's queenside would be frozen. }
12... c6
{ Hindering b5. Black usually does not want to block even further his light squared bishop, but in this case the b5-push is more threatening. Black needs to relocate his minor pieces to more active squares. }
13. a4
{ Otherwise black would play ...Nf6, maintaining the stability of the center for black. With a4, the b4-b5 threat is again black's main headache and he has to address it. }
13... a5
{ Very logical, provoking white to play b5 if he is so confident on that push, but now black would get a protected passed pawn for his troubles.  White would be in trouble if he takes the bait not only because of the a-pawn but because black's pieces would have very nice squares to work with like ...Bd6, ...Nf6 and the rooks coming to the c-file.  Most of the main attacking squares for white would be forbidden by black's pawns @@StartBracket@@ c4-c5-e4@@EndBracket@@ or pieces @@StartBracket@@ e5-c6@@EndBracket@@. }
14. bxa5
{ White can delay the exchange on a5 but he should do it at some point. Otherwise ...axb4 could be annoying for white }
14... Rxa5
{ We want to keep our structure as sound as possible while the rook on the a-file becomes active.  The main ideas for black are to place the bishop on c4 via a6 @@StartBracket@@first the a5-rook should be removed or it will be trapped@@EndBracket@@ and replace the knight and the other bishop on f6 and d6 respectively.  If white tries to exchange his a-pawn for our b-pawn, we just wait and capture on b6 with the queen, allowing this piece and the e8-rook to join the action on the queenside. }
