[Black "4.g3 with Ne5 & Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3
{ The best, and the move that is played the most by far. The bishop will be developed by g2, which allows a quick short castling, solving white's problems with the king on many of the lines already seen. }
4... Bb7
{ Now that white will counter the long diagonal directly, this move makes even more sense than in previous occasions. }
5. Bg2
{ The move that has been played the most by far, allowing white to castle and placing the bishop on its natural square. }
5... Be7
{ ...d5 is premature since there is no white knight on c3 neither the c1-bishop has been developed. There is no other sensible move than this one, also allowing black to castle on the next move. }
6. O-O
{ This move is the most logical not only for king's safety, but because now the g2-bishop is protected and white can think on moving the f3-knight without worrying about the g2-bishop. }
6... O-O
{ Like in the last move, ...d5 is still inaccurate. Black also castles before commiting in the center. }
7. Nc3
{ White keeps developing his pieces. This move reinforces the center of the board. e4 is still not possible, but d5 is a major threat. }
7... d5
{ Black must react in the center. As always in these cases, black should occupy the center with his own pawns, strengthening his central position on the squares d5 and e4. }
8. Ne5
{ The main move, seeking the initiative and freeing the main diagonal for the g2-bishop, avoiding the positions where black freed himself with ...dxc4 and waiting to develop the c1-bishop. }
8... Nbd7
{ Developing the last minor piece. This position is one of the most played in this line and also a good example of how black has to develop.  The f6-knight is ready to jump to e4 while the d7-knight will replace its fellow on f6. The bishops on e7 and b7 are ready to join the action. }
9. Bf4
{ Delaying cxd5 and defending the knight on e5 to be able to recapture with the bishop if necessary.  Also clearing the c1-square for the rook. }
9... c5
{ As on several occasions that white has developed the bishop to f4, black must break with ...c5 and accept hanging pawns on many occasions, but the resulting position is ok.  Black has nothing to win delaying this push so it is better to commit to it after Bf4 before white can arrange his pieces to the d and c-pawns.   9...c6  is also  possible but it feels too passive. }
10. cxd5 { The usual response to ...c5. } 10... Nxd5
{ All conditions are met so we can take on d5 with the knight.  Once again taking with other piece would be a mistake because black would be left with a position with less space or without central control. }
11. Nxd5
{ Otherwise black would avoid the hanging pawns by tacking on c5 with a piece as black would exchange first the knight on c3 allowing massive exchanges in the position. }
11... exd5
{ Taking with the bishop is bad because after the exchange of bishops  11...Bxd5  12.Bxd5  exd5  white can play  13.Nc6  and disrupt black's harmony, forcing  13...Qe8  and being able to reach a bishop vs knight middlegame if white prefers it. }
12. Rc1 { Placing the rook on its main square pressing the c5-pawn. } 12... g5
{ Drastic decision, but with the f6-knight out of play, this advance can be supported without any problems.  Black can either play a position a pawn up after 13. Bd2 cxd4 or a more positional approach after ...c4, closing the queenside and securing black's long-term benefits on this part of the board.  Obviously black must be careful with the way he handles the kingside but with the empty f6-square black can support the g5-pawn with both ...h6 and ...f6, securing the kingside.  It is still a very double edged position for both sides and one that has been played in few occasions.  The pawn structure is pretty clear, but it cannot be said the same on how black should arrange his pieces; it will depend on how white decides to face this aggression but the main themes for this position are to relocate the queen to f5 via d7 if possible and it is very useful to place a rook on the g7-square like in the Mar del Plata variation of the King's Indian Defense. }
