8... Nbd7
{ Developing the last minor piece. This position is one of the most played in this line and also a good example of how black has to develop.  The f6-knight is ready to jump to e4 while the d7-knight will replace its fellow on f6. The bishops on e7 and b7 are ready to join the action. }
9. f4
{ A move to take into account, but white has a worse score than black, as the center and short castle will be exposed.  Black needs to know what he is doing and play energetically to take profit of white's adventurous play. }
9... c5
{ Hitting the center now that the main pawnchain of f2-e3-d4 is no longer an option for white. ...c5 also weakens the g1-a7 diagonal for our dark squared bishop.  It is also a very coherent way of playing this since we play with this move in other positions. }
10. e3
{ Holding the center before launching the likely strike on the kingside. }
10... Rc8 { Developing the rook and aiming at the c4-pawn. } 11. f5
{ Trying to continue the advance, but the center is too compromised for it.  It has never been played, but it is a natural move according with the previous play from white. Black can achieve a good position with precise play. }
11... cxd4
{ Important intermediate move.  Black needs to clear the c5-square before any further action in white's territory. It also weakens white's central control. If black does not play it he can be in trouble in the center. }
12. exd4
{ Only sensible move. Taking first on d7 is not good because black could stabilize his center and start the assault without any compensation for white.   The engine considers the position after  12.Nxd7  as lost for white. }
12... Ne4
{ Threatening to exchange all the knights, so that white's open king will have more pressure than blacks since the f-pawn cannot create enough difficulties without the knights.  Nxd7 is almost forced and after that black should exchange some pieces to achieve the attacking position he wants. That means to keep the bishops, especially the one on e7, and open the center to take advantage of the weak white king. }
