{ This move is the most logical not only for king's safety, but because now the g2-bishop is protected and white can think on moving the f3-knight without worrying about the g2-bishop. }
6... O-O
{ Like in the last move, ...d5 is still inaccurate. Black also castles before commiting in the center. }
7. Nc3
{ White keeps developing his pieces. This move reinforces the center of the board. e4 is still not possible, but d5 is a major threat. }
7... d5
{ Black must react in the center. As always in these cases, black should occupy the center with his own pawns, strengthening his central position on the squares d5 and e4. }
8. Ne5
{ The main move, seeking the initiative and freeing the main diagonal for the g2-bishop, avoiding the positions where black freed himself with ...dxc4 and waiting to develop the c1-bishop. }
8... Nbd7
{ Developing the last minor piece. This position is one of the most played in this line and also a good example of how black has to develop.  The f6-knight is ready to jump to e4 while the d7-knight will replace its fellow on f6. The bishops on e7 and b7 are ready to join the action. }
9. Qa4
{ This is the main line that is reached if both sides play the most played move until now. White develops the queen to a4 where it covers the c6-square and leaves the d1-square for a rook.  Nc6 is a major threat that will leave black with a very bad position. Fortunately black has a move that solves all his problems. }
9... c6
{ The key move that maintains equality, and in fact, black's position is easier to play, with white having to be precise on many occasions.  But you could say that this move does not prevent white to play Nc6, since now he gets a pawn with this move! That is true, but there is a large difference: the c-file would be open and black could target the c4-pawn.  So as strange as it might sound, black's position is better without the c-pawn. }
10. Nxc6
{ Since this was white's main idea, it is a move to consider. This is the most played move in this position, albeit very close to 10. Rd1, which will be discussed later.  White considers that it is a good option to fall into black's 'trap', but although the position is ok for black, white is still in the game with a balanced position.  White will get the bishop pair. }
10... Bxc6
{ Other moves make no sense. The bishop on b7 is the one that black should exchange because it has worse prospects. }
11. Qxc6
{ Forced move. The queen is deep into enemy territory but it is safe unless white gets too greedy. }
11... Rc8
{ As said before, this is the key difference. As there is no pawn on c7, the black rook threatens the queen and black will be able to capture on c4.  The rook on c4 could seem somewhat loose, but if black knows what he is doing he should have no problems. }
12. Qa4
{ Removing the queen from the action.  It is also more accurate than 12. Qb7 in the case that white wants to capture at a7. }
12... Rxc4
{ Black has to regain the pawn before it is too late.  Otherwise white will take on d5 and remain a pawn up for no compensation. }
13. Qxa7
{ Greedy but still not punishable. White takes the a7-pawn hoping to be able to get the queen back home while black has to figure out if the d4-pawn is poisoned or not. }
13... Qc8
{ The d4-pawn can wait for now. Black first should improve his position, in this case rerouting the queen with the threat of trapping the intruder on a7.  This maneuver is only used to gain time to recover the pawn without worrying about the rook in the center of the board since if white plays the correct moves his queen will be fine. }
14. Bf4
{ One of the possible moves for white. It covers the b8-square for the rook hindering the ...b6-b5 push while it also leaves the c1-square for the rooks to join the action on the queenside. }
14... Rxd4
{ Black needs to take the pawn back. 15. b3 is not possible so the rook can always come back to c4 or go to b4.   14...Qc6?!  seems that it catches the enemy queen, but it is black who falls into a trap:  15.Rac1  Ra8?  16.Nxd5!  and everything is hanging.    Black's ideas are concentrated on the queenside, returning the rook to the c-file, activating the bishop and pushing the b-pawn to create weaknesses in white's queenside. }
