[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.g3 Main line with Rd1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3
{ The best, and the move that is played the most by far. The bishop will be developed by g2, which allows a quick short castling, solving white's problems with the king on many of the lines already seen. }
4... Bb7
{ Now that white will counter the long diagonal directly, this move makes even more sense than in previous occasions. }
5. Bg2
{ The move that has been played the most by far, allowing white to castle and placing the bishop on its natural square. }
5... Be7
{ ...d5 is premature since there is no white knight on c3 neither the c1-bishop has been developed. There is no other sensible move than this one, also allowing black to castle on the next move. }
6. O-O
{ This move is the most logical not only for king's safety, but because now the g2-bishop is protected and white can think on moving the f3-knight without worrying about the g2-bishop. }
6... O-O
{ Like in the last move, ...d5 is still inaccurate. Black also castles before commiting in the center. }
7. Nc3
{ White keeps developing his pieces. This move reinforces the center of the board. e4 is still not possible, but d5 is a major threat. }
7... d5
{ Black must react in the center. As always in these cases, black should occupy the center with his own pawns, strengthening his central position on the squares d5 and e4. }
8. Ne5
{ The main move, seeking the initiative and freeing the main diagonal for the g2-bishop, avoiding the positions where black freed himself with ...dxc4 and waiting to develop the c1-bishop. }
8... Nbd7
{ Developing the last minor piece. This position is one of the most played in this line and also a good example of how black has to develop.  The f6-knight is ready to jump to e4 while the d7-knight will replace its fellow on f6. The bishops on e7 and b7 are ready to join the action. }
9. Qa4
{ This is the main line that is reached if both sides play the most played move until now. White develops the queen to a4 where it covers the c6-square and leaves the d1-square for a rook.  Nc6 is a major threat that will leave black with a very bad position. Fortunately black has a move that solves all his problems. }
9... c6
{ The key move that maintains equality, and in fact, black's position is easier to play, with white having to be precise on many occasions.  But you could say that this move does not prevent white to play Nc6, since now he gets a pawn with this move! That is true, but there is a large difference: the c-file would be open and black could target the c4-pawn.  So as strange as it might sound, black's position is better without the c-pawn. }
10. Rd1
{ Very often used in practical play, it is an inaccuracy that leads to a very interesting position for black.  In my own practice, I feel that a lot of people that does not know the 9...c6 move, and if they start thinking in this position they usually play 10. Rd1.  The ensuing position is not only pleasant for black, but very difficult for white to grasp if he does not know about it beforehand. }
10... Nxe5
{ The next moves are forced for black to achieve a good position, but the moves are very intuitive and can even be played over the board.  The first time I faced this position with black I had no idea of the move 10. Rd1, so I had to find it over the board against an IM, and I managed to get a close-to-winning position! Although the game ended in a draw.  First, black has to remove the e5-knight to relieve black's lack of space in the center. The d4-pawn would be relocated to e5, where it does nothing and leaves the c5-square for our remaining knight.  The c6-pawn is no longer weak. }
11. dxe5
{ In practice, white always plays this move.  11.cxd5  is also possible, but it has never been played in my database. }
11... Nd7
{ Heading to the c5-square, hitting the queen. Black's center is very strong as the spearhead on d5 is perfectly secured.  The knight is also threatening to take on e5, but white should focus on securing this e5-pawn. In practical play, black almost never is able to take this pawn. }
12. cxd5
{ Only move to protect the e5-pawn, although it does not defend it directly. Other moves are worse.  White weakens black's center and no longer has to worry about a timely ...dxc4. It is the main move for white. }
12... exd5
{ 12...cxd5 is also possible, but the current move on the board is the best.  Even though it looks like the bishop is totally plugged, it is easier to mobilize the c and d-pawns in this fashion than moving only the d-pawn, which could be blocked with a piece on d4.  Black also gets the e6-square, which could be used for the knight or even the queen in some lines. }
13. e4
{ Very common, but it is another inaccuracy. Fighting for the center, but white only blocks his own bishop and it is not on his hands to open the a8-h1 diagonal. The queen cannot shift to the kingside.  Black is just better. }
13... Nc5
{ Again an only move, but it is quite intuitive. Gaining a tempo on the queen and developing the knight to an awesome square, where it hits the important d3-square and has two different routes to improve even further if needed.  The d4-pawn looked like a weakness a move ago after 13. e4, but now it will show its full potential. Taking on e5 was not an option because white could blow open the position in the center while our queen is on the same file as the enemy rook.  Black will benefit from a closed position while white wishes to open it. }
14. Qc2
{ Other moves only enable black to keep developing his pieces while attacking the queen. }
14... d4
{ Last only move to achieve a great position. The d4-pawn is very annoying and if white does not prevent them, ...Ne6 and ...c5 will improve black's position.  Black's ideas also include transferring the light squared bishop to a6 and play ...Qd7 to improve the queen and permitting the rooks to join the action on the d-file.  b4 is not a problem because the knight can retreat to a6 or e6 if needed, where it will persue new preys. White is close-to-lost. }
