[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: 4.e3 5.Bd3"]
[Black "Main line with Nb5 & Nxc7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too many trouble.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop allows black to place his black bishop on d6, where it will be more active.  Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push while it difficults white to make the same push. }
5. Bd3 { The most natural move after 4. e3, preparing a fast short castling, }
5... d5
{ If white follows this move order, it is very likely that he wants to play O-O, b3, Bb2, Nc3 and Rc1, one way or the other.  Black's plan is to play ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Nbd7 and ...a6, depending on how white develops. }
6. cxd5 exd5
{ If white wants to take right away on d5 @@StartBracket@@or at any point in this line@@EndBracket@@ black must take with the e-pawn.  This way we retain our trumps like the control over the e4-square and being able to play ...Bd6 in one move. Taking with any piece would allow the push e3-e4 at some point which would take a lot of space in the center. }
7. O-O Bd6 8. Nc3 O-O
{ Playing ...a6 before O-O is also possible, but then white could play e4 since our king would be on the center. To avoid this possibility, it is better to play ...O-O as soon as possible. }
9. Nb5
{ If white harasses our bishop, we remove it back to e7. Then, we play ...a6 and we place it back on the d6-square. }
9... Be7 10. Qc2
{ According to engines the best move for white is  10.Nc3  which told us the usefulness of  9. Nb5.  Still, we should know what to do if white continues with the idea of pressing on the queenside. }
10... a6
{ This move forces white to retreat, and we reach the main position of this chapter. }
11. Nxc7
{ White cannot take on c7 but this is the only critical move of this variation. }
11... Ra7
{ The knight is trapped, but black must be precise to keep as much pawns as possible. }
12. Bd2 h6
{ Important move because, in some lines, the h7-pawn is weak after Nxd5. The white knight is not going anywhere for now. }
13. Rac1 { For instance, holding to the knight as much as possible. } 13... Bd6
14. Rfd1 { White cannot add more pieces to defend the adventurous knight. }
14... Bc8 { Time to collect. } 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. e4
{ White has to try something direct to get some compensation. } 16... Rc7
{ A nice intermediate move. The white queen is forced to a worse square while we improve our rook. }
17. Qb1 Nf4
{ White has not enough compensation for the piece. Black can exchange one pair of rooks, ...Bg4 and ...Ne6-g5. If allowed we can exchange the knight for the light squared bishop. }
