5... d5
{ If white follows this move order, it is very likely that he wants to play O-O, b3, Bb2, Nc3 and Rc1, one way or the other.  Black's plan is to play ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Nbd7 and ...a6, depending on how white develops. }
6. O-O Bd6
{ We can play ...Bd6 since white has chosen to play very passively, and white has no way to punish us because of it. }
7. b3
{ Starting with 7. b3 makes sense if white prefers to develop his b1-knight towards d2 instead of c3. }
7... O-O { Black plays his usual plan. } 8. Bb2 Nbd7 9. Nbd2 Ne4
{ Black still wants to take the e4-square. } 10. Qc2 f5
{ Reinforcing the knight on its best square. } 11. Ne5
{ This move leads to a favorable ending for black. } 11... Bxe5
{ The following sequence is very forcing. } 12. dxe5 Nxd2
{ We are exchanging an active knight for a passive knight, but this is tactically justified. }
13. Qxd2 Nc5 { A tempo move. White has to protect the attacked bishop. } 14.
Rfd1
{ Allowing black to take on d3 is not a great idea because the bishop on b7 is clearly stronger than its counterpart. }
14... Nxd3 15. Qxd3 Qg5 16. Qf1 Rfd8
{ Black has better pieces, a better pawn structure since the majority on the kingside is not effective, while black can create a passed pawn on the queenside at will. But the main advantage for black is the bishop on b7. }
