[White "Chapter 1: 4.e3 5.Bd3"]
[Black "Main line with the e4 push #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too many trouble.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop allows black to place his black bishop on d6, where it will be more active.  Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push while it difficults white to make the same push. }
5. Bd3 { The most natural move after 4. e3, preparing a fast short castling, }
5... d5
{ If white follows this move order, it is very likely that he wants to play O-O, b3, Bb2, Nc3 and Rc1, one way or the other.  Black's plan is to play ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Nbd7 and ...a6, depending on how white develops. }
6. O-O Bd6
{ We can play ...Bd6 since white has chosen to play very passively, and white has no way to punish us because of it. }
7. Nc3 O-O 8. cxd5 { It is the second most played move. } 8... exd5 9. Qc2
{ If white plays with this move order, it only makes sense if his intention is to play e4. If white plays b3-Bb2 we reach the main line, or even a worst version of it since the Qc2-move is not the best in this case. We follow our main plan. }
9... a6
{ We cannot stop e3-e4 because now Nb5 is a real threat because the c7-pawn is weaker than in other positions. The good part is that the e4-push is not something that black should worry about. }
10. e4
{ The idea behind white's last moves.  If white plays any other move black can either play ...Re8, stopping the central break or keep developing with ...Nbd7 since the e4-push is not scary anyway.  In any case, we reach other positions showed in this chapter. }
10... dxe4
{ We must take on e4. In fact, the best response is to exchange everything in the center. }
11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Bxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Nd7 14. Bg5
{ After this sequence of forced moves white shows his cards. Bg5 is a developing move that wins a tempo on our queen.  If black is not precise he could find himself in a passive position, even if it is still equal. }
14... Re8
{ With an equal position. We continue with ...Nf6 and we try to exchange queens. }
15. Bxd8
{ If white exchanges queens, in the ensuing position only black can play for a win. }
15... Rxe4 16. Bg5 f5
{ Black's rook on e4 is cemented with the f-pawn, so we are the owners of the only open file.  Moreover, the g5-bishop will soon be expelled of its active square @@StartBracket@@...h6@@EndBracket@@ and forced to go back to d2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: 4.e3 5.Bd3"]
[Black "Main line with the e4 push #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too many trouble.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop allows black to place his black bishop on d6, where it will be more active.  Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push while it difficults white to make the same push. }
5. Bd3 { The most natural move after 4. e3, preparing a fast short castling, }
5... d5
{ If white follows this move order, it is very likely that he wants to play O-O, b3, Bb2, Nc3 and Rc1, one way or the other.  Black's plan is to play ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Nbd7 and ...a6, depending on how white develops. }
6. O-O Bd6
{ We can play ...Bd6 since white has chosen to play very passively, and white has no way to punish us because of it. }
7. Nc3 O-O 8. cxd5 { It is the second most played move. } 8... exd5 9. Qc2
{ If white plays with this move order, it only makes sense if his intention is to play e4. If white plays b3-Bb2 we reach the main line, or even a worst version of it since the Qc2-move is not the best in this case. We follow our main plan. }
9... a6
{ We cannot stop e3-e4 because now Nb5 is a real threat because the c7-pawn is weaker than in other positions. The good part is that the e4-push is not something that black should worry about. }
10. e4
{ The idea behind white's last moves.  If white plays any other move black can either play ...Re8, stopping the central break or keep developing with ...Nbd7 since the e4-push is not scary anyway.  In any case, we reach other positions showed in this chapter. }
10... dxe4
{ We must take on e4. In fact, the best response is to exchange everything in the center. }
11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Bxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Nd7 14. Bg5
{ After this sequence of forced moves white shows his cards. Bg5 is a developing move that wins a tempo on our queen.  If black is not precise he could find himself in a passive position, even if it is still equal. }
14... Re8
{ With an equal position. We continue with ...Nf6 and we try to exchange queens. }
15. Qd5
{ Or almost any other move with the queen. After  15.Qf5  Qc8  with the idea of playing  16...Nf8 is quite good. }
15... Nf6
{ Blocking the bishop and attacking the queen. If white places the queen on c6 or f5, black can play ...Qd7, breaking the pin and offering a new exchange of queens. }
16. Qc4 h6
{ Forcing the bishop to decide. With the current pawn structure it makes no sense to take on f6, since it only helps us to develop towards the weakness on d5. }
17. Bh4 Bf4
{ With ...Qd5 on the next move and the maneuver ...g5-Nh5 on the agenda. The position is balanced, but black is the one dictating the pace. }
