[White "Chapter 1: 4.e3 5.Bd3"]
[Black "Nc3 with b3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too many trouble.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop allows black to place his black bishop on d6, where it will be more active.  Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push while it difficults white to make the same push. }
5. Bd3 { The most natural move after 4. e3, preparing a fast short castling, }
5... d5
{ If white follows this move order, it is very likely that he wants to play O-O, b3, Bb2, Nc3 and Rc1, one way or the other.  Black's plan is to play ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Nbd7 and ...a6, depending on how white develops. }
6. O-O Bd6
{ We can play ...Bd6 since white has chosen to play very passively, and white has no way to punish us because of it. }
7. Nc3 O-O 8. b3
{ The most natural way of developing the dark squared bishop. } 8... Nbd7
{ 8...a6  was also possible, but as a rule of thumb we will only play ...a6 if we have finished developing the minor pieces, or white is threatening to play Nb5 and retreating with ...Be7 is not an option @@StartBracket@@for instance, if the c7-pawn is weak@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Nb5
{ We can play ...Be7, followed by the usual plans, or in this concrete position we have the following alternative. Retreating the bishop would reach the main line. }
9... dxc4 10. Nxd6
{ Not the best move, but what else? After playing 9. Nb5, if white does not take on d6 we will retreat the bishop and reach a similar position as in the main line. }
10... Bxf3
{ Important move. We do not play this line to allow white to take on c4 and chill out. }
11. Qxf3 cxd3 { White cannot reinforce the center with bxc4. } 12. Ne4 e5
{ With an equal position after exchanging knight and pawns on d4.  Black is currently a pawn up and although the d3-pawn is weak and far advanced, it is still alive and kicking. }
