9. Bb2 a6
{ ...a6 is an useful move that we want to play anyway, but as said before we usually play it after all the minor pieces are developed. }
10. Rc1 Qe7
{ Connecting the rooks and waiting for white to decide how he wants to continue. }
11. Na4
{ The most popular move in this position. White is preparing to play Ne5. This move is also activating the c1-rook if black plays ...c5. }
11... dxc4
{ The only inconvenient of the previous move is that the knight no longer controls the e4-square. And black take advantage of it. }
12. bxc4 c5
{ With a balanced position. Now white cannot open the c-file for the rook, as cxd5 is no longer an option. The game could continue with: }
13. Ne5
{ If white plays  13.dxc5  bxc5  and the a4-knight is still out of the game. }
13... Rfd8 14. Qe2 Rac8 15. Rfd1 Bc7
{ After improving the rooks, black is thinking about exchanging the knights on e5. But before that, we play ...Bc7, which overprotects the b6-pawn and leaves the d-file open for the rook. }
