{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push while it difficults white to make the same push. }
5. Bd3 { The most natural move after 4. e3, preparing a fast short castling, }
5... d5
{ If white follows this move order, it is very likely that he wants to play O-O, b3, Bb2, Nc3 and Rc1, one way or the other.  Black's plan is to play ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Nbd7 and ...a6, depending on how white develops. }
6. O-O Bd6
{ We can play ...Bd6 since white has chosen to play very passively, and white has no way to punish us because of it. }
7. Nc3 O-O 8. b3
{ The most natural way of developing the dark squared bishop. } 8... Nbd7
{ 8...a6  was also possible, but as a rule of thumb we will only play ...a6 if we have finished developing the minor pieces, or white is threatening to play Nb5 and retreating with ...Be7 is not an option @@StartBracket@@for instance, if the c7-pawn is weak@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Bb2 a6
{ ...a6 is an useful move that we want to play anyway, but as said before we usually play it after all the minor pieces are developed. }
10. Rc1 Qe7
{ Connecting the rooks and waiting for white to decide how he wants to continue. }
11. cxd5
{ After this move we reach a typical position that can be reached via lots of different move orders. For this reason this is the critical response in this position, as black players will face this move more often. }
11... exd5
{ Taking with the pawn is the best option if white has left his dark squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This way black has a better control of the e4-square as moves like ...Ne4 comes to mind. }
12. Ne2
{ Trying to replace the knight which does nothing on c3 and blocks the other white pieces. }
12... Ne4 13. Qc2 Rac8
{ We protect the c7-pawn with the rook, so the e5-square is protected and the knight cannot jump to the center. It is just a mild change from the main line, with Qc2 and ...Rac8 included. We can play as in the main line without any further analysis. }
