[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 2: 4.e3 5.Nc3 | 5.a3 | 5.Sidelines"]
[Black "5.Nc3 Bb5+ with Ba4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too many trouble.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop allows black to place his black bishop on d6, where it will be more active.  Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push while it difficults white to make the same push. }
5. Nc3
{ With this move order, we will probably reach the same positions as in the previous chapter with  5.Bd3  .  There is no difference if white plays Bd3 first and then Nc3 or the other way around.   In this chapter I will focus on the only difference that matter in this move order: the white bishop can check us with Bb5+ before retreating to d3.  This line has to be treated separately since its ideas are different from the main line seen on the previous chapter. }
5... d5
{ As said on the introduction chapter, we play ...d5 when white is threatening to expand in the center with e4 or d5. In that case, we play ...d5 ourselves to avoid it. }
6. cxd5 exd5
{ In this case we will take with the pawn because our dark squared bishop hasn't move yet, so we can place it on d6 right away.  With this settings @@StartBracket@@mainly the c1-bishop being stuck inside white's pawn chain@@EndBracket@@ ...exd5 reach a nice structure for black. Moreover, the Bb5+ with the knight on d5 is slightly awkward.Moves like Bd3, Be2, b3 or Ne5 leads to the main lines seen on the 5. Bd3 chapter. With this move order the only relevant move is 7. Bb5+. }
7. Bb5+
{ This check provokes ...c6. The downside of this move is that it blocks the bishop on b7, which loses control over the e4-square. So white can open the center with a timely e3-e4.  On the upside, black no longer needs to spend a tempo on ...a6 because the c6-pawn performs the same role of preventing Nb5. }
7... c6
{ This sequence is not forced, but most of the times it reaches the same position. }
8. Ba4
{ This move makes no sense, but it is not terrible and has been played by one top player, so it deserves our attention. White will not play for the e4-push for now. }
8... Bd6 { We will develop as usual. } 9. O-O O-O 10. Ne5
{ The main idea. White wants to take the center with the knight and reinforce it with f4. This is the only way of playing this position for white that makes sense. }
10... b5 { Gaining as much space as possible on the queenside. } 11. Bc2 Re8
12. f4 Nbd7
{ Black will play on the queenside, pushing his pawns up the board. ...Qb6 and ...Ba6 are the main moves for black. Also the break ...c5 has to be considered. }
*

