{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too many trouble.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop allows black to place his black bishop on d6, where it will be more active.  Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push while it difficults white to make the same push. }
5. a3
{ It is an interesting move, with the idea of expanding on the queenside as soon as possible. It is a very rare move, but it is the more complex after 4. e3. }
5... d5
{ We want to place the dark squared bishop on d6. Thus we have to play ...d7-d5 to be able to play our desired setup. }
6. Nc3
{ This is the most played move in this position by far. In a lot of cases transposes to some main line: }
6... Nbd7
{ We delay the ...Bd6 move because white can respond with b4 and c5. Delaying the development of the bishop we are saving the option of playing ...a7-a5 after 7. b4.  After this waiting move white has to decide, and in every case black has a good response to get a comfortable position. In a lot of cases will transpose to a main line. For instance: }
7. b4 { Since the bishop is still at home, black is not worried about c4-c5. }
7... a5
{ And we play as in the main line of this chapter. Probably this will lead to some transposition. }
*

