[Black "5.a3 6.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too many trouble.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop allows black to place his black bishop on d6, where it will be more active.  Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push while it difficults white to make the same push. }
5. a3
{ It is an interesting move, with the idea of expanding on the queenside as soon as possible. It is a very rare move, but it is the more complex after 4. e3. }
5... d5
{ We want to place the dark squared bishop on d6. Thus we have to play ...d7-d5 to be able to play our desired setup. }
6. Nc3
{ This is the most played move in this position by far. In a lot of cases transposes to some main line: }
6... Nbd7
{ We delay the ...Bd6 move because white can respond with b4 and c5. Delaying the development of the bishop we are saving the option of playing ...a7-a5 after 7. b4.  After this waiting move white has to decide, and in every case black has a good response to get a comfortable position. In a lot of cases will transpose to a main line. For instance: }
7. Bd3
{ This is the move that does not transpose to a main line.  After white has developed the light squared bishop @@StartBracket@@either Bd3 or Be2@@EndBracket@@, black can play ...dxc4 at any moment without giving white a free tempo.  If white plays b4 in the following moves, trying to push with c4-c5, black just plays ...dxc4 and that's it. }
7... Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. b4 dxc4
{ Black has a good position where white's expansion on the queenside is not making any progress. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 2: 4.e3 5.Nc3 | 5.a3 | 5.Sidelines"]
[Black "5.a3 6.b4! with cxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too many trouble.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop allows black to place his black bishop on d6, where it will be more active.  Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push while it difficults white to make the same push. }
5. a3
{ It is an interesting move, with the idea of expanding on the queenside as soon as possible. It is a very rare move, but it is the more complex after 4. e3. }
5... d5
{ We want to place the dark squared bishop on d6. Thus we have to play ...d7-d5 to be able to play our desired setup. }
6. b4
{ Moves like 6. Nc3 or 6. Bd3 doesn't make sense because this are a waste of time regarding the main lines. In that case we will play as in the main lines @@StartBracket@@ ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Nbd7, ...Ne4,...@@EndBracket@@6. b4 has been played a very few times, so I will show some ways of how the game could continue. }
6... a5
{ Attacking the queenside expansion right away. White has to react to the threat of ...axb4. }
7. cxd5
{ Taking on d5 before black can do it. On this sideline I will focus on the position that can arise after white plays this central capture. }
7... exd5 8. b5 Ne4
{ White wants to play Nc3 and we hinter it. Other developing moves like ...Nbd7 or ...Bd6 are also fine but this bother white a little more. }
9. Bd3 Bd6
{ The usual development of this bishop in this kind of positions with an early e3. }
10. O-O Nd7 11. a4 Qe7
{ White most likely will play Ba3 at some point to exchange our powerful bishop on d6. When that happens, we want to take back with the queen so we can develop the queen right now. We also keep our options open about where to place the king. }
12. Ba3 O-O-O
{ The queenside is blocked, so the black king will be safe on the b8-square. The only weak point is the c7-pawn, but we can protect it with the queen and the rook. }
13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Ra2 Kb8
{ White is not threatening us, but moving the king to safety is always good prophylactic thinking. }
15. Rc2 Rc8
{ The position is balanced, but black's plan is very simple: attack on the kingside. Meanwhile, it is not easy to suggest a way for white to attack the black king. If needed, black can bring an extra defender with ...Nf8-e6. }
