{ We want to place the dark squared bishop on d6. Thus we have to play ...d7-d5 to be able to play our desired setup. }
6. b4
{ Moves like 6. Nc3 or 6. Bd3 doesn't make sense because this are a waste of time regarding the main lines. In that case we will play as in the main lines @@StartBracket@@ ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Nbd7, ...Ne4,...@@EndBracket@@6. b4 has been played a very few times, so I will show some ways of how the game could continue. }
6... a5
{ Attacking the queenside expansion right away. White has to react to the threat of ...axb4. }
7. bxa5
{ Exchanging this pawns favors black. The a8-rook becomes active and white's structure has been compromised. Still, the position remains equal, although I prefer black. }
7... Rxa5 { The a-file is an asset for black. } 8. Bd2 Ra8 9. cxd5
{ White wants to develop the bishop without losing a tempo after ...dxc4. }
9... exd5
{ Taking with the pawn to achieve the ideal setup with ...Bd6 and ...Ne4. } 10.
Bd3 Bd6
{ Black has a comfortable position. Right now, the b1-knight cannot develop since the a3-pawn would be hanging. }
