[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too many trouble.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop allows black to place his black bishop on d6, where it will be more active.  Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push while it difficults white to make the same push. }
5. a3
{ It is an interesting move, with the idea of expanding on the queenside as soon as possible. It is a very rare move, but it is the more complex after 4. e3. }
5... d5
{ We want to place the dark squared bishop on d6. Thus we have to play ...d7-d5 to be able to play our desired setup. }
6. b4
{ Moves like 6. Nc3 or 6. Bd3 doesn't make sense because this are a waste of time regarding the main lines. In that case we will play as in the main lines @@StartBracket@@ ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Nbd7, ...Ne4,...@@EndBracket@@6. b4 has been played a very few times, so I will show some ways of how the game could continue. }
6... a5
{ Attacking the queenside expansion right away. White has to react to the threat of ...axb4. }
7. b5 { Solving the a-file problem for good. } 7... Nbd7 { Keep developing. }
8. Nc3 { White can develop the knight before black plays ...Ne4. } 8... Ne4
{ Black can seize the center anyway. } 9. Qb3 Nxc3 10. Qxc3 dxc4
{ 10...Bd6  would allow  11.c5!  since  after taking everything on c5, white could play Qxg7. So black takes on c4 and achieves the ideal position with ...Bd6 and ...O-O. }
11. Bxc4 Bd6 { With an equal position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 2: 4.e3 5.Nc3 | 5.a3 | 5.Sidelines"]
[Black "5.a3 6.b4! 7.b5 with 8.Bb2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too many trouble.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop allows black to place his black bishop on d6, where it will be more active.  Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push while it difficults white to make the same push. }
5. a3
{ It is an interesting move, with the idea of expanding on the queenside as soon as possible. It is a very rare move, but it is the more complex after 4. e3. }
5... d5
{ We want to place the dark squared bishop on d6. Thus we have to play ...d7-d5 to be able to play our desired setup. }
6. b4
{ Moves like 6. Nc3 or 6. Bd3 doesn't make sense because this are a waste of time regarding the main lines. In that case we will play as in the main lines @@StartBracket@@ ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Nbd7, ...Ne4,...@@EndBracket@@6. b4 has been played a very few times, so I will show some ways of how the game could continue. }
6... a5
{ Attacking the queenside expansion right away. White has to react to the threat of ...axb4. }
7. b5 { Solving the a-file problem for good. } 7... Nbd7 { Keep developing. }
8. Bb2
{ The move cxd5 is a possibility in all this moves, but it makes no difference with the sideline 7. cxd5 on this chapter. So in the following lines I will focus on the positions where white does not capture on d5. }
8... Ne4 9. Nbd2 Nxd2
{ For black is good to exchange one pair of knight since there is only one good square for black's knights: the e4-square. Therefore black only needs one knight to occupy this square.  Exchanging a pair of minor pieces will help us as black has less space due to white's expansion on the queenside. }
10. Qxd2 Bd6 { The usual suspect. } 11. cxd5 exd5
{ Every time that white takes on d5, we recapture with the e-pawn, and we follow it like we did on the 7. cxd5 line, with ...Qe7 and ...O-O-O.  We are not afraid of reaching this positions since it is the most comfortable for black. }
