1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3
{ Not too common, and also not a critical attempt. It is not a bad move, but the black player can develop freely without too many trouble.  Playing e3 before developing the c1-bishop allows black to place his black bishop on d6, where it will be more active.  Thanks to that, black will reach a comfortable position with all winning chances. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push while it difficults white to make the same push.  In this last lines of 4. e3, we will check some alternative moves for white on the 5th move, but neither are a critical attempt.  In fact, all sensible moves that white can play in this position will transpose one way or the other to a mainline/sideline, so this means that this last lines are probably the least important of all. }
