{ Developing the bishop before playing e3. The bishop also pins the knight on f6 hence e2-e4 and d4-d5 are possible. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push, while it makes it difficult for white to make this same push. }
5. e3
{ With the c1-bishop outside the pawn chain we need to be careful when we have to play ...d5 and when it is not necessary.Since the lines with 4. Bg5 and 4. Nc3 & 5. Bg5 are closely related, in this chapter we will analyse mainly the variants where white plays with e3. The lines where white tries to play without e3 will be discussed in a future chapter. }
5... Be7
{ First, we break the pin in order to reactivate the knight. Since white has not developed the b1-knight yet, ...d7-d5 is premature. So the bishop move is also useful in that sense, waiting for white to show his hand. }
6. Nc3 O-O 7. Bd3
{ This is the main position of this line. 7. Bd3 is the most played move far away from the second  @@StartBracket@@ Be2@@EndBracket@@. White just wants to develop his last minor piece and find a safe place for the king. }
7... d5
{ Taking the center before white does it. Black had no other move to postpone this move, but white's knight is on c3 so black is ready to take on d5 with the knight. }
8. O-O { The top choice for white players. } 8... Nbd7
{ Following the typical plan. } 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12.
Qc2 { Threatening two pawns, and supporting the e4-push. } 12... Bxf3
{ Only move, but a good one. } 13. gxf3 c5
{ After the exchange black still has two pawns under fire. The h7-pawn is not important, so we save the c7-pawn, activating black's pieces.     We can save both pawns with  13...Nf6  , but after  14.Rac1  black's position is too passive. }
14. Bxh7+ { What else? } 14... Kh8 15. Be4 Rac8
{ With plenty of compensation for the pawn. White should be careful.  The rook will go to the h-file with the queen to harass the king. }
*

