[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Bg5
{ Developing the bishop before playing e3. The bishop also pins the knight on f6 hence e2-e4 and d4-d5 are possible. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to the fianchetto square. From here, the bishop aims at the e4-square and supports the d5-push, while it makes it difficult for white to make this same push. }
5. e3
{ With the c1-bishop outside the pawn chain we need to be careful when we have to play ...d5 and when it is not necessary.Since the lines with 4. Bg5 and 4. Nc3 & 5. Bg5 are closely related, in this chapter we will analyse mainly the variants where white plays with e3. The lines where white tries to play without e3 will be discussed in a future chapter. }
