[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: 4.Bf4"]
[Black "Main line 6.Nc3 transposition #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Bf4
{ Similar to the London System. With the pawn on c4, it is not as stable as the usual London. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to b7 before anything else. It is not necessary, but still the most logical move and this way we are always playing the same fourth move. }
5. Nc3
{ The main alternative, delaying e3. This moves is already deciding on how white will react to ...Bb4. }
5... Bb4
{ We still develop the bishop to b4. In this case, we are pinning the knight on c3. }
6. e3 Ne4 { It transposes to the main line after 5.e3 6.Nc3. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: 4.Bf4"]
[Black "Early Nc3 with a fast a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Bf4
{ Similar to the London System. With the pawn on c4, it is not as stable as the usual London. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to b7 before anything else. It is not necessary, but still the most logical move and this way we are always playing the same fourth move. }
5. Nc3
{ The main alternative, delaying e3. This moves is already deciding on how white will react to ...Bb4. }
5... Bb4
{ We still develop the bishop to b4. In this case, we are pinning the knight on c3. }
6. a3 { Natural but wrong. } 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6
{ We reached a very typical structure in the Nimzo-Indian Defence with one important difference: the dark squared bishop is on f4. Black's plan is the usual in this positions: ...Nbd7, ...Qe7 and push ...e5.  Since black has lost his dark squared bishop, he plans to place most of his pawns on dark squares. This way black's surviving bishop will be active.  Also the enemy dark squared bishop will only hit protected pawns and remain useless. On f4 the bishop is not doing anything and will be hit by ...e6-e5, losing a tempo. }
8. e3 Nbd7 9. Bd3 Qe7 { Black's plan is effective and unstoppable. } 10. Bg5 e5
11. Bc2 h6
{ Keeping the bishop alive allowing ...g7-g5 is no better. Therefore white's best choice is to trade on f6. }
12. Bxf6 Nxf6 { Black has a much better pawn structure. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: 4.Bf4"]
[Black "Early Nc3 with 6.Qb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Bf4
{ Similar to the London System. With the pawn on c4, it is not as stable as the usual London. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to b7 before anything else. It is not necessary, but still the most logical move and this way we are always playing the same fourth move. }
5. Nc3
{ The main alternative, delaying e3. This moves is already deciding on how white will react to ...Bb4. }
5... Bb4
{ We still develop the bishop to b4. In this case, we are pinning the knight on c3. }
6. Qb3
{ 6. e3 is the main move, but it would transpose to the main line. So we need to see some alternatives that does not involve the e-pawn. }
6... Qe7
{ This move is a novelty in this position, but this position has been reached once in other move order. }
7. e3 Ne4
{ Since we have to exchange our bishop anyway, let's make sure we also damage the pawn structure. }
8. Bd3 Bxc3+
{ White is threatening moves like Qc2 and c5 that could be problematic, so we take on c3 at the first chance. The most important thing is to wreck the pawn structure. }
9. bxc3 d6
{ Achieving the kind of position we want. In this case, white did not play a3, so white has an extra move to improve his position. }
10. c5
{ White must play this move at some point to improve his structure @@StartBracket@@or worsen ours@@EndBracket@@. White can delay this move, but it does not benefit him. }
10... dxc5 11. O-O O-O
{ With an equal position. Black should play normally with moves like ...Nbd7 and rooks to d8 and c8.  The c7-pawn is not important and black can just give it back in exchange for fast development, or play ...cxd4 immediately and ...c7-c5 next, depending on the situation and the player's preference. }
