1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Bf4
{ Similar to the London System. With the pawn on c4, it is not as stable as the usual London. }
4... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to b7 before anything else. It is not necessary, but still the most logical move and this way we are always playing the same fourth move. }
5. e3 { The most played by far. Hiding white's intentions over the b1-knight. }
5... Bb4+
{ In this position we play slightly different. This check disturbs white's development. }
6. Nbd2 O-O
{ 6...Ne4 does not make that much sense. The knight on d2 is now safe and we can not take advantage of that.   On the other hand, the d2-knight is more passive on d2, so black can take advantage of that in the long run. }
7. Bd3
{ He wants to play e4. We had previously seen that when they threaten us with e4 @@StartBracket@@or d5@@EndBracket@@, we would respond with ... d5, but in this case there is another way to avoid e4, taking advantage of the bishop's position. }
7... Nh5 8. Bg3 { The bishop must retreat. } 8... g6
{ White has not castled short, so opening the h-file is too dangerous. With ... g6, the h5-knight can wait for the right moment without having to watch out for discovered attacks with Ne5. }
9. a3 Be7
{ After a3 we retreat the bishop to e7. It makes no sense to trade the bishop if we cannot damage white's pawn structure. If white does not threaten the bishop we can play ...d5-Nxg3 @@StartBracket@@with short castling included@@EndBracket@@ and place it directly on d6. }
10. Qe2 { White wins nothing of delaying O-O. } 10... c5
{ White has no control in the center, so we can play ...c5 with no fear of a d5 expansion. }
11. O-O cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Nc6
{ Equal position, but I prefer black's chances. Black has the bishop pair and a healhty structure. Black can continue with ...Bf6 and ...Qe7, centralizing the rooks on the d and c-files.  If white plays Nxc6, we recapture with the d-pawn and we play ...c5 as soon as possible to reactivate the b7-bishop. }
