{ In this position we play slightly different. This check disturbs white's development. }
6. Nfd2
{ Counterintuitive, but it is the main line. None of the possible cover moves are bad, but in all of them @@StartBracket@@ Nfd2, Nc3 and Nbd2 @@EndBracket@@ white's position has some disadvantage.  This is why 4. Bf4 is not a very precise move, even if the resulting position remains balanced. }
6... O-O 7. a3 Be7
{ We should retreat the bishop. Taking on d2 only helps white's development. }
8. Nc3 d5 9. cxd5 { The mostly played move by far. } 9... Nxd5
{ We can play ...Nxd5. } 10. Nxd5 { Only move played in practice. } 10... exd5
{ This position is similar to other lines of the QID, but the d2-knight is badly placed. White will spend some tempi moving this knight to an useful square. }
11. b4 { Stopping ...c5. } 11... c5 { Or maybe not. } 12. bxc5 bxc5
{ Black's plans are to relocate the bishop on b7  @@StartBracket@@now it is within reach of a Rb1 or Qb1@@EndBracket@@, either on a6 or c6, and to contest the diagonal to the bishop on f4 with ...Bd6.  The bishop will go to a6 to fight for the f1-a6 diagonal followed with ...Nxa6 @@StartBracket@@ 13. Qb1 avoids it, since after the exchanges on a6 there is ...Qb7! that wins a piece@@EndBracket@@ to recycle it via c7-e6, or else it can be developed on c6.  The game can continue: }
13. Qb1 Qb6 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Bd3 Ba6
{ Sacrificing the h7-pawn but delaying castling. } 16. Bxh7+ Kh8 17. Bd3 Qxb1+
18. Bxb1 Nc6 19. Ba2 Ne7
{ The white pieces are less coordinated, and the white king is still in the center. The position is roughly equal despite the missing pawn. Black can play ...d4 to open the position, and the-a3 pawn is under fire. }
*

