[White "Chapter 5: 4.Nc3 5.Bg5"]
[Black "With Qc2 before Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3
{ A logical move. It is also one of the most flexible moves since white can still transpose to lines with Bg5, g3, a3 or even e3. }
4... Bb7 { The usual reply. In this case fighting directly against d5 and e4. }
5. Qc2
{ This is an alternative that reaches different outcomes. It is a rare sideline. }
5... Bb4 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ Black will ruin white's structure with either ...Bxc3 or ...Bxf3. } 8. O-O-O
Bxc3 9. Qxc3 d6
{ Black's pieces make more sense. The b7-bishop is more active than its counterpart. The d7-knight would control key squares like c5 and e5.   The queen is already active on f6. Finally the black king @@StartBracket@@after O-O or O-O-O@@EndBracket@@ will be safer than the king on c1 since the c-pawn is already advanced. }
