1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3
{ A logical move. It is also one of the most flexible moves since white can still transpose to lines with Bg5, g3, a3 or even e3. }
4... Bb7 { The usual reply. In this case fighting directly against d5 and e4. }
5. Qc2
{ This is an alternative that reaches different outcomes. It is a rare sideline. }
5... Bb4 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3
{ Taking with the pawn is bad.   7.bxc3  makes no sense, as white has a worse structure and the c2-queen is a wasted move. }
7... O-O 8. e3
{ The usual reply for white. Bg5 could be played, but since white has no control over the e4-square, black can play ...d6-Nbd7-Qe7 and ...e5 if needed. White players prefer to develop the bishop via b2. }
8... d5 9. b3 Nbd7
{ Black will play ...c5, hitting white's center. If white takes on d5 at some point, we can take back with the bishop since the e4-square is controlled. }
10. Be2 Rc8 { With an equal position. } *

