1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3
{ A logical move. It is also one of the most flexible moves since white can still transpose to lines with Bg5, g3, a3 or even e3. }
4... Bb7 { The usual reply. In this case fighting directly against d5 and e4. }
5. Bg5
{ Other moves transpose to lines that have been analyzed in other chapters  @@StartBracket@@mainly a3, e3 and g3@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Be7
{ Breaking the pin. We also play this move because if white wants to play 6. e3 we transpose to known territory. }
6. Bxf6
{ It is strange to take on f6 immediately without provocation, but it is also possible. }
6... Bxf6 7. e4 { The main idea. } 7... d6
{ White has the center, but black has the bishop pair and an uncompromised structure. }
8. Be2 { We play like in the Bd3 line. } 8... Nd7 9. O-O O-O 10. Qc2 c5
{ White does not win anything with the bishop on e2. We can argue that on d3 the bishop at least was overprotecting the center. }
11. d5 Qe7 { Keeping the tension in the center. } 12. Rad1 Rad8
{ Black's ideas are ...a6 preparing ...b5, ...g6-Bg7, ...Rfe8 and transferring the knight to f6 or exchanging it on e5. Just playing the same moves as in the line with Bd3. }
