[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3
{ A logical move. It is also one of the most flexible moves since white can still transpose to lines with Bg5, g3, a3 or even e3. }
4... Bb7 { The usual reply. In this case fighting directly against d5 and e4. }
5. Bg5
{ Other moves transpose to lines that have been analyzed in other chapters  @@StartBracket@@mainly a3, e3 and g3@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Be7
{ Breaking the pin. We also play this move because if white wants to play 6. e3 we transpose to known territory. }
6. Qc2 h6
{ Forcing a decision. The direct 6...d5 is possible, but I prefer the positions after ...h6 }
7. Bxf6 { It makes more sense after ...h6. } 7... Bxf6 8. e4
{ Only logical follow up. } 8... d6
{ Black is controlling all the central squares on the fifth rank. The bishop will retreat to g7, where it will protect the king while also attacking white's queenside. }
9. Be2
{ If white wants to O-O we just keep developing. The next following moves are mandatory for black anyway @@StartBracket@@ Nd7, O-O, g6, Bg7@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Nd7 10. O-O O-O 11. Rad1 g6
{ A balanced position. Black has less space, but it's not a big deal.  If white plays d5 we should exchange the dark squared bishop before we play ...e5. If white doesn't play d5, black's ideas are ...Qe7 and ...c5. }
