[White "Chapter 5: 4.Nc3 5.Bg5"]
[Black "Main line with Bxf6, e4 & 0-0-0 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3
{ A logical move. It is also one of the most flexible moves since white can still transpose to lines with Bg5, g3, a3 or even e3. }
4... Bb7 { The usual reply. In this case fighting directly against d5 and e4. }
5. Bg5
{ Other moves transpose to lines that have been analyzed in other chapters  @@StartBracket@@mainly a3, e3 and g3@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Be7
{ Breaking the pin. We also play this move because if white wants to play 6. e3 we transpose to known territory. }
6. Qc2 h6
{ Forcing a decision. The direct 6...d5 is possible, but I prefer the positions after ...h6 }
7. Bxf6 { It makes more sense after ...h6. } 7... Bxf6 8. e4
{ Only logical follow up. } 8... d6
{ Black is controlling all the central squares on the fifth rank. The bishop will retreat to g7, where it will protect the king while also attacking white's queenside. }
9. O-O-O { White can choose between O-O and O-O-O. This is more aggressive. }
9... Nd7 10. h4 O-O
{ We still play our usual plan. ...O-O-O is not an option since then black would be easily suffocated by white's space advantage. Black's best plan is to play with opposite castle.If white tries to attack our king right away. }
11. g4 { White is creating more problems for himself than to black. } 11... g6
{ If white keeps pushing his kingside pawns we can close the position @@StartBracket@@  12.h5  g5  for instance@@EndBracket@@. }
12. Qd2 Bg7
{ The kingside is fairly safe, so after this few preparatory moves we can start the attack. }
13. d5
{ This is the only move for white to keep the balance. The idea of this move is to take en passant on c6 after ...c5 to keep the center open. With the center closed black's attack on the queenside is flowing faster. }
13... c5 { The position remains balanced, but white should be very careful. }
14. dxc6 { The best, otherwise white is in trouble. } 14... Bxc6 15. Qxd6
{ The most obvious move at a first glance. It is a mistake. } 15... Bxc3
{ Ruining white's structure on the queenside. } 16. Qxc6
{ The critical attempt. Black has two pieces hanging. } 16... Qf6
{ Both sides have pieces hanging, but black's king is safer.  17.bxc3  reaches a known position after  Qxc3+  . }
17. Qxd7 { If white takes the knight. } 17... Bxb2+
{ Protecting the bishop with check. A very useful move in this position in almost all lines. }
18. Kb1 Rad8
{ According to the engine the best move for white is  19.Be2  . I think this is self-explanatory.   19.Qa4  , protecting the e1-rook is not enough after  Qxf3  , hitting both rooks and indirectly defending the b2-bishop. }
*

