1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3
{ A logical move. It is also one of the most flexible moves since white can still transpose to lines with Bg5, g3, a3 or even e3. }
4... Bb7 { The usual reply. In this case fighting directly against d5 and e4. }
5. Bg5
{ Other moves transpose to lines that have been analyzed in other chapters  @@StartBracket@@mainly a3, e3 and g3@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Be7
{ Breaking the pin. We also play this move because if white wants to play 6. e3 we transpose to known territory. }
6. Qc2 h6
{ Forcing a decision. The direct 6...d5 is possible, but I prefer the positions after ...h6 }
7. Bh4 { The most common reply. } 7... d5
{ Now that the bishop has decided, we can play ...d5. The position is essentially the same, but we have added the move ...h6 that could be useful later on. }
8. e3
{ Playing like this only makes sense if white does not want to commit in the center with e4. Therefore it makes little sense to play cxd5 next if black can recapture with the knight first and then with the bishop.  In that case, e3-e4 would be a waste of time, and allowing the bishop to stay on d5 unopposed is not in white's interests. }
8... O-O 9. Bxf6
{ After black has commited in the center, white wants to exchange the knight. }
9... Bxf6 10. cxd5
{ Now, ...Nxd5 is no longer available and we have to take with the pawn. }
10... exd5
{ Transposing to a position similar to the chapter 4.Bg5. Black plays for ...c5 to open the position for the bishops. }
