14... Ra8 { The rook goes back to the a-file since now it is open. } 15. Qc7
Rfc8 16. Qf4 Rc2
{ Getting the same themes as in the line with Qf4 directly. White will drop the b2-pawn anyway, and the a3-pawn  is falling. After 17. Rb1 even ...Rxb2! is playable, but ...Ba2 is the safer option.  Both moves leads to an equal position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 6: 4.a3 5.Nc3 6.Qa4 | 6.Qc2 | 6.Bf4"]
[Black "7.cxd5 9.Qc2 with 10.Bg5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3
{ The second move most played. White prevents ...Bb4+, which indirectly bolsters his position in the center. This means that black will commit faster in the center with ...d5, which could cause some trouble for us. }
4... Bb7
{ 4. a3 does not pose any immediate threat, so we can develop the bishop normally. }
5. Nc3
{ ...Bb4 is no longer an option, so the knight comes to c3. This is the most logical move. Other moves @@StartBracket@@like 5. e3@@EndBracket@@ transposes to lines that have been already analysed. White wants to play d5 so we need to stop it. }
5... d5
{ White wants to play d5, so we need to stop it. In this case, as ...Bb4 is not an option, the move for black has to be ...d5 again. In this position white has many options to carry out the game towards calmer or more stormy fields. }
6. Qa4+
{ White is forcing black to take a decision on how to stop this check. If black blocks it with a piece or a pawn, it will be pinned and useles for some time.  If black blocks it with the queen, white can exchange queens early on, leading to a position that will be hard to unbalance. According to computer this is the best move.  Still, very few games feature this position. }
6... Nbd7
{ Since we want to play this move anyway, we play it now. This weakens the c6-square, but white cannot take advantage of it.  If white could play Bb5 it could also be annoying, but since the bishop is still unable to move there is no problem. }
7. cxd5
{ The main idea. The main threat for black was ...dxc4, freeing his position and enabling some fast development on the queenside with ...a6-b5. Taking on d5 just solve this problem. }
7... Nxd5 { The white knight is on c3, so we can recapture with the knight. }
8. Nxd5 Bxd5 { No need to block our bishop. } 9. Qc2
{ White brings back the queen since the job has been done on a4. The reason why the engine prefers to play Qa4 and Qc2, instead of Qc2 in one move, is quite obscure.  It turns out that if we play the same line with 6. Qc2 @@StartBracket@@instead of 6. Qa4+@@EndBracket@@ black does not play 6...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@6...Be7 is more natural@@EndBracket@@ and black would be able to take on d5 with the queen. In that case, the queen on d5 is well placed and black is more active than in the current position.White threatens e4, so we have to deal with it. }
9... f5
{ Preventing e4 and reinforcing the e4-square for the knight or the bishop. }
10. Bg5 Be7
{ Blocking with the bishop makes more sense than self-pinning with ...Nf6. }
11. Bxe7 Qxe7
{ With the idea to bring the knight to e4 and break with ...c5. White can take on c7, but white will not be able to keep the extra pawn. }
12. Qxc7 O-O 13. e3 Rac8 { 13...Rfc8 is also possible. } 14. Qf4 Rc2
{ Regaining the pawn. White can castle and we get an equal position. } *

