{ Next we will analyze two moves that do not link together with a3, but that have been played a lot in this position. Neither of them is too incisive, so we reach a playable position for both sides.  White achieves nothing tangible with this moves. Unfortunately, these are moves that do not worsen white's position, so gaining an advantage will be difficult. }
6. Qc2
{ This line is quite predictable according to databases, because white always plays it the same way. }
6... Be7 7. cxd5 { 90% of games with this move. } 7... Nxd5 8. Bd2
{ White plays in a similar way but wants to recapture on c3 with the bishop. }
8... O-O 9. e4 Nxc3 10. Bxc3 c5
{ White's dark squared bishop is more active, but the d4-pawn is weaker. We will play like in the line with 8. e4, developing the queenside and supporting the ...c5-break. }
11. dxc5
{ The main move and the main difference over the main line.  After dxc5 white's queenside structure is not scattered, so in this line white can do this. }
11... bxc5
{ But we do not care about isolated pawns since we can easily defend the c5-pawn from behind. This pawn controls the d4-square and the b4-break. In some cases, we can even advance it to gain more space. }
12. Rd1 Qc7 13. Bd3 c4
{ A new move, taking the d3-square from white. Our pieces will orbit this pawn with a rook on c8 and the knight going to b6. The position is equal and all results are possible. }
