[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 6: 4.a3 5.Nc3 6.Qa4 | 6.Qc2 | 6.Bf4"]
[Black "6.Bf4 with 7.Bg3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3
{ The second move most played. White prevents ...Bb4+, which indirectly bolsters his position in the center. This means that black will commit faster in the center with ...d5, which could cause some trouble for us. }
4... Bb7
{ 4. a3 does not pose any immediate threat, so we can develop the bishop normally. }
5. Nc3
{ ...Bb4 is no longer an option, so the knight comes to c3. This is the most logical move. Other moves @@StartBracket@@like 5. e3@@EndBracket@@ transposes to lines that have been already analysed. White wants to play d5 so we need to stop it. }
5... d5
{ Next we will analyze two moves that do not link together with a3, but that have been played a lot in this position. Neither of them is too incisive, so we reach a playable position for both sides.  White achieves nothing tangible with this moves. Unfortunately, these are moves that do not worsen white's position, so gaining an advantage will be difficult. }
6. Bf4
{ Similar to the 'fake London System' that we have seen in another chapter. In this case ...Bb4 is not possible for obvious reasons on a3. So we have to figure out other plan. }
6... Bd6 { Opposing the enemy bishop. } 7. Bg3 O-O
{ We are not in a hurry to capture on g3. We are not worried of Bxd6 neither, so we keep developing. }
8. e3 c5
{ Since we cannot develop the knight as we want we strike on the center. } 9.
Qc2
{ If white is not reacting in the center we can start exchanging. White's king is still on e1 and we can profit from it. }
9... Bxg3 10. hxg3 cxd4 11. Nxd4 dxc4
{ With an uncomfortable attack on g2 that prevents white from castling short. The queenside looks too open for the king, but it may be its best option. We also have an extra pawn for now.White will try to attack on the kingside with his pawns, and we have to stop it. A preventive ...h6 is useful and if we can place the b8-knight on f8 we will be protected.  White's king on the queenside will be very open, and we can attack it with ...a6 and ...b5 at the right time. }
