{ 4. a3 does not pose any immediate threat, so we can develop the bishop normally. }
5. Nc3
{ ...Bb4 is no longer an option, so the knight comes to c3. This is the most logical move. Other moves @@StartBracket@@like 5. e3@@EndBracket@@ transposes to lines that have been already analysed. White wants to play d5 so we need to stop it. }
5... d5
{ White wants to play d5, so we need to stop it. In this case, as ...Bb4 is not an option, the move for black has to be ...d5 again. In this case, we are going to fight against 6. Bg5. }
6. Bg5
{ Second most played move in this position. Pinning the knight to prevent ...Nxd5. }
6... Be7 { Breaking the pin and enabling short castling. } 7. Qa4+
{ Asking black how he wants to cover himself, which can lead to the exchange of queens. }
7... Qd7 8. Qc2
{ The maneuver Qa4-c2 has forced black to move his queen to d7, where it is on the way of the b8-knight. Also threatens 9. Ne5, attacking the misplaced queen. }
8... dxc4
{ Preventing Ne5 because the d4-pawn would be hanging. After Qa4-Qc2 white has lost a tempo, and now we can support the c4-pawn with ...b5. }
9. e3
{ White threatens to regain the pawn, but since the queen was forced to moved to d7 we can protect it for now. }
9... Bxf3
{ 10. Ne5 was the major threat so we remove it. Then, we will defend the b5-pawn. }
10. gxf3 b5 { With this maneuver, we can hold on to the extra pawn. } 11. Bxf6
{ White must regain the pawn, and for this he must give away the bishop pair. Bxf6, a4 and Qe4 can be done in different move orders but they lead to the same position. }
11... Bxf6 12. Qe4 O-O 13. a4 { Main move to disrupt black's queenside. } 13...
c6
{ The rook on a8 was in danger. After a4 we have to play ...c6 to stop axb5. }
14. axb5 cxb5 { The rook is still untouchable for the same reasons as before. }
15. f4
{ It is also playable, but this line requires precision. Some moves are very difficult if you don't know them in advance. }
15... Rc8 16. Bh3
{ Important move, in the following moves of white it will be seen why. } 16...
Nc6
{ The b5-pawn is immune due to ...Nb4 followed by ...Nd3+. To be clear:   17.Nxb5  Nb4  18.Nc3  Nd3+  . }
17. O-O Rab8 18. d5
{ Only move to keep the balance. The main idea after 16. Bh3.It leads to massive changes that simplify the position altogether. }
18... Nd8 19. Rfd1 Qb7
{ Placing the queen on a better spot. We will exchange queens if needed. } 20.
dxe6 Nxe6 { First we take the pawn. Otherwise exf7+ wins a pawn. } 21. Bxe6
Qxe4 22. Bxf7+ { A logical move, winning the f7-pawn before taking the queen. }
22... Kxf7 23. Nxe4 Bxb2
{ After 22. Bxf7+ we have an extra move, and we use it to take the b2-pawn. The c4-pawn is fast. }
24. Rd7+
{ The incorrect check.   24...Kf8  would transpose to the main line after  25.Raxa7  . But we do not need to do it }
24... Kg6 25. Raxa7 b4
{ The pawns are running while our king is safe. The bishop can go to f6 to block the checks if needed. }
*

