[White "Chapter 7: 4.a3 5.Nc3 6.Bg5"]
[Black "7.e3 Main line with 12.dxc5 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3
{ The second move most played. White prevents ...Bb4+, which indirectly bolsters his position in the center. This means that black will commit faster in the center with ...d5, which could cause some trouble for us. }
4... Bb7
{ 4. a3 does not pose any immediate threat, so we can develop the bishop normally. }
5. Nc3
{ ...Bb4 is no longer an option, so the knight comes to c3. This is the most logical move. Other moves @@StartBracket@@like 5. e3@@EndBracket@@ transposes to lines that have been already analysed. White wants to play d5 so we need to stop it. }
5... d5
{ White wants to play d5, so we need to stop it. In this case, as ...Bb4 is not an option, the move for black has to be ...d5 again. In this case, we are going to fight against 6. Bg5. }
6. Bg5
{ Second most played move in this position. Pinning the knight to prevent ...Nxd5. }
6... Be7 { Breaking the pin and enabling short castling. } 7. e3
{ The main line. White just reinforces the center, and most importantly, allow the f1-bishop to go out and enable O-O.   If  7.cxd5  , it usually transposes to this main line. }
7... O-O 8. Rc1 Nbd7 9. cxd5 exd5 { We take with the pawn because c7 is weak. }
10. Bd3 Ne4
{ We have been forced to play ...exd5 so we take advantage of it. The knight on e4 is strong. }
11. Bf4 c5 12. dxc5
{ Critical move, although it has never been played and has some flaws. } 12...
Nxc3 13. Rxc3 bxc5 14. O-O
{ By transposition, we reached a position that had been played before. } 14...
c4
{ Normally it is not good to decide so quickly when you have hanging pawns, but in this case black can take advantage of the rook on c3 to buy time. Black's main moves are Bf6 and Nc5. }
15. Bf5 Bf6
{ The attack on the c3-rook, and the pawn on b2 is more difficult to handle than it appears at first glance.Natural moves for white lead to a good position for black. }
16. Qc2 { The best move, attacking h7. } 16... h6
{ We have to save the pawn first. } 17. Nd4 Nc5 18. b4 { Only move. } 18...
cxb3 19. Qc1 b2
{ Getting an extra tempo. The b2-pawn is easier to defend than the pawn on b3. }
20. Qc2 Ne6
{ Forcing a reaction. White has some options, but he has to be careful. The rook is still on c3. }
21. Bxe6 fxe6 22. Nxe6
{ Once again, it is not good. The weak rook on c3 and the pawn on b2 are a bigger threat. }
22... Qb6
{ Attacking the knight and supporting the pawn on b2 with the queen. } 23. Rb3
{ We lose the bishop pair, but we are winning anyway. } 23... Qxe6 24. Rxb7
Rac8 { First, we improve our rook. } 25. Qb1 Qe4
{ White's best move is  26.Rxb2  , so there is little else to say about this position. }
