1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3
{ The second move most played. White prevents ...Bb4+, which indirectly bolsters his position in the center. This means that black will commit faster in the center with ...d5, which could cause some trouble for us. }
4... Bb7
{ 4. a3 does not pose any immediate threat, so we can develop the bishop normally. }
5. Nc3
{ ...Bb4 is no longer an option, so the knight comes to c3. This is the most logical move. Other moves @@StartBracket@@like 5. e3@@EndBracket@@ transposes to lines that have been already analysed. White wants to play d5 so we need to stop it. }
5... d5
{ White wants to play d5, so we need to stop it. In this case, as ...Bb4 is not an option, the move for black has to be ...d5 again. In this case, we are going to fight against 6. Bg5. }
6. cxd5
{ The most played move in this positions. Most of the times this move ends up transposing to previous lines. }
6... Nxd5 { Knight on c3 = we take on d5 with the knight. } 7. Bd2
{ This one is a new move. Intending to play Bxc3. } 7... Nd7
{ White wants to take on c3 with the bishop to activate it. So, Nxd5 is not a priority for white, and we can develop meanwhile. }
8. Qc2 { Protecting the e4-square. } 8... c5
{ Striking in the center before white has its control. } 9. Nxd5
{ This is by no means a mistake, but it is counter-intuitive with white's previous play. }
9... exd5
{ White could control the center with 10. e4, so we are forced to take with the pawn on d5. }
10. dxc5
{ The most logical move, since white wants to place the bishop on c3. It makes no sense to allow black to play ...c4 and keep the diagonal closed. }
10... bxc5 11. e3 Bd6
{ Since the c3-knight is gone, the pressure on d5 is lower and Nb5 is not available. In this case, we can play ...Bd6, where the bishop is more active. }
12. Bd3 h6 { Necessary before castling. } 13. O-O O-O
{ With an equal position. } *

