[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 10: 4.g3 - White plays 7.Re1 & 8.cxd5"]
[Black "10.b3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3
{ The best move, and the one that is played the most by far. The bishop will be developed by g2, which allows a quick short castling. This solves white's problems with the king and early development. }
4... Bb7
{ Placing the bishop on the long diagonal at the first opportunity. The fight for the long diagonal is one of the most important in this position.It is important to notice that while the bishop on g2 will be defended with the king, the bishop on b7 most of the time will be unprotected. Therefore we need to be careful about anything happening on the long diagonal. }
5. Bg2
{ Other moves just end up transposing anyway. White wants to fight for the long diagonal as soon as possible and play O-O. }
5... Be7
{ Developing one more piece and allowing ...O-O. 5...d5 is not a good move since white is delaying Nc3. }
6. O-O
{ Swiftly hiding the king and protecting the g2-bishop. The rook can also be developed. }
6... O-O
{ Doing the same as white. White's knight is still at home so ...d5 is flawed. }
7. Re1 { Interesting move, delaying Nc3 for the moment. } 7... d5
{ One of the few times where we play ...d5 without following the rules @@StartBracket@@the knight on c3 or the dark squared bishop on f4@@EndBracket@@. White is not threatening e4 for now, but we are running out of useful moves to delay committing in the center.So, why is ...d5 now not a bad move? The main reason is because Re1 is a one-dimensional move; it threatens to play e4, but nothing else.The knight on c3 is not only planning to play e4, but it is also pressing on d5 and can jump to b5 to attack c7. It is also cleaning the way for the a1-rook to come to the c-file. }
8. cxd5 { The main idea for white and the move we have to counter. } 8... exd5
{ White has forced us to take on d5 with the pawn. In exchange white has played Re1, which once the e4-push is no longer possible looks as a wasted move. So, we can say that white has lost one tempo to worsen black's setup. }
9. Nc3
{ Other moves just transposes, since 10. Nc3 is the most played move if it is not played on move 9. }
9... Nbd7
{ Now, it is time to develop the last minor piece. Black follows the usual plan. }
10. b3
{ It looks like white has not a clear plan. b3 after Re1 does not work together, since it does nothing towards the center. }
10... Re8
{ Pushing e3-e4 for white is out, and black can play as usual and get a fine position. }
11. Bb2 Ne4 12. Rc1 a5
{ With an equal position. The b2-bishop is not a great piece. } *

