{ One of the few times where we play ...d5 without following the rules @@StartBracket@@the knight on c3 or the dark squared bishop on f4@@EndBracket@@. White is not threatening e4 for now, but we are running out of useful moves to delay committing in the center.So, why is ...d5 now not a bad move? The main reason is because Re1 is a one-dimensional move; it threatens to play e4, but nothing else.The knight on c3 is not only planning to play e4, but it is also pressing on d5 and can jump to b5 to attack c7. It is also cleaning the way for the a1-rook to come to the c-file. }
8. cxd5 { The main idea for white and the move we have to counter. } 8... exd5
{ White has forced us to take on d5 with the pawn. In exchange white has played Re1, which once the e4-push is no longer possible looks as a wasted move. So, we can say that white has lost one tempo to worsen black's setup. }
9. Nc3
{ Other moves just transposes, since 10. Nc3 is the most played move if it is not played on move 9. }
9... Nbd7
{ Now, it is time to develop the last minor piece. Black follows the usual plan. }
10. Bf4 { The most played move by far. } 10... Ne4 11. Rc1
{ Threatening c7 indirectly. } 11... Nxc3
{ We exchange one pair of knights. This way, we remove some tactics on c7 and we anyway only need one knight to take the e4-square. }
12. bxc3 { Strengthening the center and feigning with playing c4 if possible. }
12... Re8
{ Developing the rook and leaving the f8-square for the bishop or the knight. Fighting for the e4-square. This is almost a novelty, with only one game on the database. }
13. Qb3 c5 { Time to go forward. We run out of useful developing moves. } 14.
dxc5 Nxc5
{ White just gave us free tempos to improve our pieces. It makes no sense to play like that. }
15. Qb2 Bf6
{ Black is just better thanks to the free moves that allowed us to seize the initiative. }
