{ One of the few times where we play ...d5 without following the rules @@StartBracket@@the knight on c3 or the dark squared bishop on f4@@EndBracket@@. White is not threatening e4 for now, but we are running out of useful moves to delay committing in the center.So, why is ...d5 now not a bad move? The main reason is because Re1 is a one-dimensional move; it threatens to play e4, but nothing else.The knight on c3 is not only planning to play e4, but it is also pressing on d5 and can jump to b5 to attack c7. It is also cleaning the way for the a1-rook to come to the c-file. }
8. cxd5 { The main idea for white and the move we have to counter. } 8... exd5
{ White has forced us to take on d5 with the pawn. In exchange white has played Re1, which once the e4-push is no longer possible looks as a wasted move. So, we can say that white has lost one tempo to worsen black's setup. }
9. Nc3
{ Other moves just transposes, since 10. Nc3 is the most played move if it is not played on move 9. }
9... Nbd7
{ Now, it is time to develop the last minor piece. Black follows the usual plan. }
10. Bf4 { The most played move by far. } 10... Ne4 11. Rc1
{ Threatening c7 indirectly. } 11... Nxc3
{ We exchange one pair of knights. This way, we remove some tactics on c7 and we anyway only need one knight to take the e4-square. }
12. bxc3 { Strengthening the center and feigning with playing c4 if possible. }
12... Re8
{ Developing the rook and leaving the f8-square for the bishop or the knight. Fighting for the e4-square. This is almost a novelty, with only one game on the database. }
13. Qb3 c5 { Time to go forward. We run out of useful developing moves. } 14.
a4
{ A useful addition, widening the board. Now, we should worry of a4-a5 in some positions. }
14... Bf8 { Retreating the bishop to activate the rook. } 15. e4
{ The critical move. Black has to be careful, but he can reach an even position. Ng5 is a possibility to attack the f7-pawn if we open the a2-g8 diagonal. }
15... Rxe4 { It is better to exchang the active rook on e1 first. } 16. Rxe4
dxe4 17. Ng5 { Going back makes no sense. } 17... Qf6
{ The best move. The reason is showed after the very logical 18. Nxe4. } 18.
Nxe4 Qf5
{ Attacking on e4 and preventing d5. A key move on this position. If black does not know this maneuver placing the queen on f5 is very likely that black plays 17...Qe7?! }
19. Qb1 { The only move that gives an edge to white according to the engine. }
19... Rd8
{ We need some precise moves to avoid uncomfortable problems. Eyeing at d4. }
20. a5 { Weakening our queenside. } 20... Qg6
{ Holding the pin and overprotecting the b6-pawn. } 21. axb6 axb6 22. Rd1 cxd4
{ Stopping d4-d5. } 23. Rxd4 Bc6 { Solving the pin problem. } 24. Qd1 Ra8
{ Reaching an even position. Rxd7 is not possible due to the weakness of the first rank combined with the e4-knight, which would be left unprotected.   25.Rxd7?!  Bxd7  26.Qxd7?  is the final mistake,   White has to play  26.Nf6!  Qxf6  27.Bxa8  Qxc3!  and the position is around equal  28.Qxd7  Qa1+  .  Ra1+!  27.Bf1  Qxe4  with a winning position for black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 11: 4.g3 - White plays 7.Re1 & 8.Ne5"]
[Black "9.cxd5 with 12.Qd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3
{ The best move, and the one that is played the most by far. The bishop will be developed by g2, which allows a quick short castling. This solves white's problems with the king and early development. }
4... Bb7
{ Placing the bishop on the long diagonal at the first opportunity. The fight for the long diagonal is one of the most important in this position.It is important to notice that while the bishop on g2 will be defended with the king, the bishop on b7 most of the time will be unprotected. Therefore we need to be careful about anything happening on the long diagonal. }
5. Bg2
{ Other moves just end up transposing anyway. White wants to fight for the long diagonal as soon as possible and play O-O. }
5... Be7
{ Developing one more piece and allowing ...O-O. 5...d5 is not a good move since white is delaying Nc3. }
6. O-O
{ Swiftly hiding the king and protecting the g2-bishop. The rook can also be developed. }
6... O-O
{ Doing the same as white. White's knight is still at home so ...d5 is flawed. }
7. Re1 { Interesting move, delaying Nc3 for the moment. } 7... d5
{ One of the few times where we play ...d5 without following the rules @@StartBracket@@the knight on c3 or the dark squared bishop on f4@@EndBracket@@. White is not threatening e4 for now, but we are running out of useful moves to delay committing in the center.So, why is ...d5 now not a bad move? The main reason is because Re1 is a one-dimensional move; it threatens to play e4, but nothing else.The knight on c3 is not only planning to play e4, but it is also pressing on d5 and can jump to b5 to attack c7. It is also cleaning the way for the a1-rook to come to the c-file. }
8. Ne5
{ It is not very popular, but black has to be careful. The long diagonal is open and the b7-bishop is unprotected. Consequently, ...dxc4 is not an option. }
8... Nbd7
{ Usually, we will play ...Nbd7 after white has came forward with his knight to e5. In this case, ...c5 is also possible, but this move could reach different positions from the repertoire. }
9. cxd5 exd5
{ Following our rule with the knight on c3, in this case we take with the pawn. }
10. Nc3 Nxe5
{ We take on e5 in the positions when white has already played cxd5. } 11. dxe5
Ne4 12. Qd3 { If white does not take on e4. } 12... Bb4
{ We will exchange the bishop for the c3-knight. This way, the e4-knight will be strong in the center of the board. With an equal position. }
*

