{ Both players have a passed pawn, but black's pawn seems more dangerous. Also, the d-pawn is under enemy fire and could fall shortly, while the c-pawn is not currently receiving any attacks. The game could continue with: }
17. d5 { Only move or the black pawns have the advantage. } 17... Rfe8 18. a3
{ Here black has two options: going for a calm position or a crazy one. } 18...
Rxe5 { The most incisive move. } 19. axb4 Bxd5 20. Qd4 Qf5
{ And white has nothing better than to take on d5 and c4.  The position is equal, but black can get a passed pawn on the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 11: 4.g3 - White plays 7.Re1 & 8.Ne5"]
[Black "Main line with 11.Nxd5 & 13.Bxe5 #6 sacrifice alternative #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3
{ The best move, and the one that is played the most by far. The bishop will be developed by g2, which allows a quick short castling. This solves white's problems with the king and early development. }
4... Bb7
{ Placing the bishop on the long diagonal at the first opportunity. The fight for the long diagonal is one of the most important in this position.It is important to notice that while the bishop on g2 will be defended with the king, the bishop on b7 most of the time will be unprotected. Therefore we need to be careful about anything happening on the long diagonal. }
5. Bg2
{ Other moves just end up transposing anyway. White wants to fight for the long diagonal as soon as possible and play O-O. }
5... Be7
{ Developing one more piece and allowing ...O-O. 5...d5 is not a good move since white is delaying Nc3. }
6. O-O
{ Swiftly hiding the king and protecting the g2-bishop. The rook can also be developed. }
6... O-O
{ Doing the same as white. White's knight is still at home so ...d5 is flawed. }
7. Re1 { Interesting move, delaying Nc3 for the moment. } 7... d5
{ One of the few times where we play ...d5 without following the rules @@StartBracket@@the knight on c3 or the dark squared bishop on f4@@EndBracket@@. White is not threatening e4 for now, but we are running out of useful moves to delay committing in the center.So, why is ...d5 now not a bad move? The main reason is because Re1 is a one-dimensional move; it threatens to play e4, but nothing else.The knight on c3 is not only planning to play e4, but it is also pressing on d5 and can jump to b5 to attack c7. It is also cleaning the way for the a1-rook to come to the c-file. }
8. Ne5
{ It is not very popular, but black has to be careful. The long diagonal is open and the b7-bishop is unprotected. Consequently, ...dxc4 is not an option. }
8... Nbd7
{ Usually, we will play ...Nbd7 after white has came forward with his knight to e5. In this case, ...c5 is also possible, but this move could reach different positions from the repertoire. }
9. Nc3 c5 10. cxd5 { As always... } 10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 exd5
{ We take with the pawn. We do not allow e4. } 12. Bf4
{ Again 12. Nxd7 reaches the position where white played 10. Nxd7. White is preparing to take on e5 with the bishop. It also frees the c1-square for the rook. }
12... Nxe5 { Exchanging the active knight. } 13. Bxe5 c4
{ With the knight on e5 we cannot play this because white can play Nxc4! since the bishop on c7 is unprotected.White has to react on the queenside before we can reinforce it. }
14. b3 Qd7 { Protecting the bishop and connecting the rooks. } 15. bxc4 Bb4
{ Winning one tempo on the rook before taking back the pawn. } 16. Rf1 dxc4
{ Both players have a passed pawn, but black's pawn seems more dangerous. Also, the d-pawn is under enemy fire and could fall shortly, while the c-pawn is not currently receiving any attacks. The game could continue with: }
17. d5 { Only move or the black pawns have the advantage. } 17... Rfe8 18. a3
{ Here black has two options: going for a calm position or a crazy one. } 18...
Rxe5 { The most incisive move. } 19. axb4 Bxd5 20. f4
{ The rook cannot leave the fifth rank. } 20... Qb7
{ With enough compensation for the exchange. } 21. fxe5 Bxg2 22. Rf2 Bh3 23.
Qd4 Be6
{ With options for both sides. Black has a bishop and a pawn for the exchange, but white's doubled pawns on the e-file are stuck. In fact, the e6-bishop controls these pawns, defends the only weak point of black's castling on f7 and supports the queenside advance. }
*

