{ Placing the bishop on the long diagonal at the first opportunity. The fight for the long diagonal is one of the most important in this position.It is important to notice that while the bishop on g2 will be defended with the king, the bishop on b7 most of the time will be unprotected. Therefore we need to be careful about anything happening on the long diagonal. }
5. Bg2
{ Other moves just end up transposing anyway. White wants to fight for the long diagonal as soon as possible and play O-O. }
5... Be7
{ Developing one more piece and allowing ...O-O. 5...d5 is not a good move since white is delaying Nc3. }
6. O-O
{ Swiftly hiding the king and protecting the g2-bishop. The rook can also be developed. }
6... O-O
{ Doing the same as white. White's knight is still at home so ...d5 is flawed. }
7. b3
{ In this kind of position, the b2-bishop does not participate much. It is better to develop this bishop to f4 or g5. The difference with the b7-bishop is that black can play ...dxc4 to open the diagonal when it suits him.In contrast, white depends on black playing ...c5 or ...dxc4 in order to activate his bishop. So, he does not depend on himself to activate the b2-bishop in most cases. Black will only play ...c5 or ...dxc4 when it benefits us.  In this line, black doesn't need to know too much theory. Black just has to place the pieces in logical squares and we get a good position. }
7... d5
{ In the seventh move we run out of waiting-developing moves. Thus, we have to decide how to proceed in the center. As usual, we play ...d5. }
8. Bb2 { The top move, logically. } 8... dxc4
{ In this position, white cannot recapture on c4 with a knight or control the center properly @@StartBracket@@e.g. e2-e4@@EndBracket@@. Therefore, we can play ...dxc4. }
9. bxc4 c5 10. dxc5
{ Taking on c5 is not a great idea. White's queenside will be very weak. }
10... Bxc5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Nbd2 Nbd7 { The knights will go to e4 and f6/c5. }
13. Rfd1 Bf8 14. a4 Nc5
{ Already going to the good squares.  Black is comfortably better, with a better structure and more active pieces. }
15. a5 { It is hasty but critical. The game could continue: } 15... bxa5 16.
Rxa5 Nb3 { Taking advantage of the pinned knight. } 17. Rb5 Nxd2 18. Rxd2 Ba6
{ We prefer to exchange rooks on d8. The c4-pawn is falling. } 19. Rxd8 Rxd8
20. Ra5 Rd1+ 21. Bf1 Bxc4 { Extra pawn for black and better pieces. } *

