{ This is the moment when it makes the most sense to play d5, after castling. White gives up a pawn to uncoordinate black's pieces and seize the space advantage.  To regain control of the position, black most likely will have to return the pawn. }
7... exd5
{ We have to accept the pawn. Otherwise, white will have a better position for no compensation. }
8. Nh4
{ Activating the g2-bishop, and the knight is addressing to the f5-square. }
8... c6 { Holding the extra pawn. } 9. cxd5 Nxd5
{ No need to ruin our pawn structure. We want to play ...d7-d5 to free our position. }
10. Nf5 Nc7
{ The best way to break free is to play ...d5. First, the knight must be removed from this square. The c7-knight seems strange, but from this square it can reach e6 @@StartBracket@@defending g7@@EndBracket@@ and leaves the f6-square for the bishop. }
11. e4 d5 { To develop the queenside pieces as soon as possible. } 12. Qg4
{ Interesting, not messing around and starting a direct attack on the kingside. A critical attempt. }
12... Bf6 { Black will continue with ...Nd7 or ...Bc8. } 13. Nc3 Nd7
{ Going to e5. } 14. Rd1 Ne5 15. Qh3
{ Only move or white worsens his position. It is a novelty. } 15... g6
{ Since it has never been played, I show some lines of how it could continue: }
16. f4 gxf5
{ If we can take the f5-knight in exchange for one of our minor pieces, we accept it.  The f5-knight is the most dangerous piece in white's attack, removing it is benefitial for us. }
17. fxe5 Bxe5 18. Qxf5 Qf6
{ White must exchange queens, so there is no more pressure. } 19. Qxf6 Bxf6 20.
Bf4 Rac8
{ With an equal position. White should be thinking about regaining the missing pawn before it is too late. }
