{ Other moves just end up transposing anyway. White wants to fight for the long diagonal as soon as possible and play O-O. }
5... Be7
{ Developing one more piece and allowing ...O-O. 5...d5 is not a good move since white is delaying Nc3. }
6. O-O
{ Swiftly hiding the king and protecting the g2-bishop. The rook can also be developed. }
6... O-O
{ Doing the same as white. White's knight is still at home so ...d5 is flawed. }
7. d5
{ This is the moment when it makes the most sense to play d5, after castling. White gives up a pawn to uncoordinate black's pieces and seize the space advantage.  To regain control of the position, black most likely will have to return the pawn. }
7... exd5
{ We have to accept the pawn. Otherwise, white will have a better position for no compensation. }
8. Nh4
{ Activating the g2-bishop, and the knight is addressing to the f5-square. }
8... c6 { Holding the extra pawn. } 9. cxd5 Nxd5
{ No need to ruin our pawn structure. We want to play ...d7-d5 to free our position. }
10. Nf5 Nc7
{ The best way to break free is to play ...d5. First, the knight must be removed from this square. The c7-knight seems strange, but from this square it can reach e6 @@StartBracket@@defending g7@@EndBracket@@ and leaves the f6-square for the bishop. }
11. e4 d5 { To develop the queenside pieces as soon as possible. } 12. Nc3 Bf6
{ With this move we protect g7 in advance, hinder the e4-e5 advance and prepare to take on c3 if needed.We do not take on e4 since in that case black's pieces would remain piled up on the queenside. The main action is happening on the kingside and we cannot waste any time. }
13. exd5 { Recovering the pawn. White settles for an ending. } 13... Nxd5
{ This way we force one extra exchange. } 14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. Bf4
{ Not exchanging too many pieces. } 15... Bxb2 { We can take another pawn. }
16. Rb1 Bf6 17. Re1 Na6 { Developing the knight and releasing the a8-rook. }
18. Bd6 Re8 { We can play this move now. } 19. Qg4 g6 20. Nh6+
{ And the best thing for white is repeating with Nh6-Nf5. Otherwise, white is worse. }
20... Kg7 21. Nf5+ Kg8 { We cannot defend the f7-pawn, so we have to repeat. }
*

