7... d5 { After Nc3 we can play ...d5 without any worries. } 8. cxd5
{ Second most played move in this position. Along with  8.Ne5  , these two moves are the top choices for black by far. }
8... Nxd5 { There is a knight on c3 so we recapture with the knight. } 9. Nxd5
exd5
{ Taking with the b7-bishop is also possible. We take with the pawn to reach the positions with hanging pawns. This way, we keep consistency with the rest of the repertoire. }
10. Bf4
{ The main idea of white's previous play. White is aiming at the c7-pawn. Black must prepare to play ...c5 and play with hanging pawns. }
10... Nd7 11. Rc1 { Other moves just delay the main plan. } 11... c5
{ We go for it. } 12. dxc5 { The usual reply for white. } 12... bxc5 13. Ne1
{ Repositioning the knight to d3 and maybe f4. Also activating the light squared bishop. This is a typical maneuver in this kind of positions. }
13... Nb6
{ Since white is going to play Nd3, ...Qb6 is not attacking on b2. So, we place the knight on b6, and this way the f6-square is free for the bishop. }
14. b3 { Delaying c4. } 14... Re8
{ Now black has to develop the rooks. c8 and e8 are the better squares, attacking the e2-pawn and protecting the pawn on c5. }
15. Nd3 Rc8
{ White is pressing in the center, but black can play ...c4 to recapture with the knight. ...Ba6 also helps in that quest.   In the case that white bothers the c8-rook with  16.Bh3  ,  Rc6  solves the problem. }
16. Rc2 Ba6 { The d5-pawn is well protected. The bishop is more active on a6. }
17. Bh3 Ra8 { With the bishop on a6 the pawn on e2 is weak. } 18. Qc1 c4
{ Most of white's pieces are aiming at c5. With this move, we solve our problems on this square. }
19. bxc4 Nxc4
{ If white takes on c4, we capture back with the knight. Otherwise, 20. Ne5 is annoying. }
