[White "Chapter 16: 4.g3 - White plays 8.Ne5 & 9.cxd5"]
[Black "10.Nxd5 with 11.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3
{ The best move, and the one that is played the most by far. The bishop will be developed by g2, which allows a quick short castling. This solves white's problems with the king and early development. }
4... Bb7
{ Placing the bishop on the long diagonal at the first opportunity. The fight for the long diagonal is one of the most important in this position.It is important to notice that while the bishop on g2 will be defended with the king, the bishop on b7 most of the time will be unprotected. Therefore we need to be careful about anything happening on the long diagonal. }
5. Bg2
{ Other moves just end up transposing anyway. White wants to fight for the long diagonal as soon as possible and play O-O. }
5... Be7
{ Developing one more piece and allowing ...O-O. 5...d5 is not a good move since white is delaying Nc3. }
6. O-O
{ Swiftly hiding the king and protecting the g2-bishop. The rook can also be developed. }
6... O-O
{ Doing the same as white. White's knight is still at home so ...d5 is flawed. }
7. Nc3
{ The most logical move. White is developing the knight on its best square. e2-e4 and d4-d5 are looming. }
7... d5 { After Nc3 we can play ...d5 without any worries. } 8. Ne5
{ The main move. White is seeking the initiative, freeing the long diagonal for the g2-bishop. This move avoids the positions where black freed himself with ...dxc4. }
8... Nbd7
{ After Ne5 we will usually respond with ...Nbd7. This way we are ready to exchange the knight on e5 if we need to. }
9. cxd5 { We have to check this move always. } 9... Nxd5
{ There is a knight on c3, so we take with the knight. It is true that now the long diagonal is open and the b7-bishop remains unprotected, but ...Nxc3 would hit the queen on d1. }
10. Nxd5 exd5
{ We have to take with the pawn. With the long diagonal open, white can either play e4, or Nc6 first and then e4. In both cases, white has the space advantage and black cannot react properly. }
11. Bf4 Nxe5
{ With the knight about to leave the board we can take on e5 more comfortably. This way dxe5 is not attacking our pieces and we have some extra time to consolidate. }
12. Bxe5 Qd7 { Protecting the bishop on b7 in advance. It also stops Bh3. } 13.
Qc2 Rac8 { Our plan is the same. First we prepare, and then we go ...c7-c5. }
14. Rfc1 c5
{ With an equal position. If white does not take on c5, we play ...c5-c4. Otherwise, we are headed to the hanging pawns position.  In some cases, the move ...g7-g5! could bother white since the e5-bishop has few squares to hide. }
*

