{ There is a knight on c3, so we take with the knight. It is true that now the long diagonal is open and the b7-bishop remains unprotected, but ...Nxc3 would hit the queen on d1. }
10. Nxd5 exd5
{ We have to take with the pawn. With the long diagonal open, white can either play e4, or Nc6 first and then e4. In both cases, white has the space advantage and black cannot react properly. }
11. Nd3
{ Saving the knight and placing it on a very good square. On d3 it controls c5 and e5, can move to f4 if necessary and does not block the g2-bishop. It supports a queenside expansion with b4. }
11... Re8 { Eyeing e4 and leaving the f8-square for the bishop or the knight. }
12. Bf4 c5
{ No reason to wait. With the knight on d3, ...c5-c4 is even better for us. }
13. Rc1 c4 { We can expand on the queenside. } 14. Ne5 b5 15. b3 Nxe5
{ As usual, it is good for black to exchange this knight. It even has moved more times than usual.  The pawnchain on the queenside was also in danger. }
16. Bxe5 { The natural recapture is a mistake. } 16... Qd7
{ Black has consolidated on the queenside. White is far away with his attack which has not even started yet.   If white plays  17.bxc4  we take back with  dxc4  . Our queenside is far ahead and black is close to winning. }
