{ Doing the same as white. White's knight is still at home so ...d5 is flawed. }
7. Nc3
{ The most logical move. White is developing the knight on its best square. e2-e4 and d4-d5 are looming. }
7... d5 { After Nc3 we can play ...d5 without any worries. } 8. Ne5
{ The main move. White is seeking the initiative, freeing the long diagonal for the g2-bishop. This move avoids the positions where black freed himself with ...dxc4. }
8... Nbd7
{ After Ne5 we will usually respond with ...Nbd7. This way we are ready to exchange the knight on e5 if we need to. }
9. Qa4
{ This is the main position. According to the databases, white scores more than 80% in this position, but this is because the most played response from black is a mistake.White threatens to play Nc6, winning the bishop pair and blocking the c-pawn. Black cannot allow this because black often depends on the ...c5 move to free himself. The d5-pawn would also be weak, as the b7-bishop would be exchanged. }
9... c6
{ The key move that maintains equality. In fact, black's position is easier to play. White has to be precise on many occasions. }
10. cxd5
{ The safest option. It is used especially if white is interested in a draw or did not know the move 9...c6.The resulting position is even and it is very easy to play for both sides. It does not require theoretical knowledge on the part of the black player because the moves are very logical and natural.  Still, I have to show something! }
10... Nxe5
{ Removing the more active piece first. This way, Nxc6 and Nxd7 are removed. }
11. dxe5
{ In this case, we can allow dxe5 hitting our knight because we are jumping to d5. }
11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5 exd5
{ Even if ...exd5 puts another pawn in front of the b7-bishop, it is actually easier to open the long diagonal with this structure.  ...d5-d4 is easier to play with a supporting pawn on c6 and is more difficult to block. The e6-square remains empty so it can be used for a piece, probably the queen. }
13. Rd1 Qc7 14. Bf4 g5
{ Perhaps black's most difficult move to make, but it is safe in this case. We have already seen this move in other lines. So, it is a move that can be noticed for the black player. }
15. Bd2 { Only move. The bishop is going to c3. } 15... Qxe5
{ We are already open on the kingside. If we are going to suffer, do it for a pawn. }
16. Bc3 Qe6
{ This position looks scary for black, but it is all under control. } 17. e4
{ White is openining the position to activate his pieces. White is also forced to make some only moves to remain equal. }
17... Bf6 { Countering the c3-bishop. } 18. Rac1
{ White cannot avoid the exchanges. } 18... Bxc3
{ If white does not exchange the bishops, we do it. } 19. Rxc3 dxe4
{ Exchanging a pair of rooks is good for black to relieve the pressure. This way the exposed kingside is less dangerous.   White cannot avoid the exchanges. The game can continue: }
20. Bxe4 Rad8
{ We trade a pair of rooks. This way, the g5-pawn is stronger because there are less pieces to attack it. }
21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. Re3 Qf6
{ Sidestepping the discovered attack. Attacking b2 and f2. } 23. Qxa7 Bc8 24.
Qxb6
{ We are a pawn down. We have to activate our pieces. White is also taking some risks. }
24... Rd2 25. Rf3
{ At first I thought this was a natural move, but it is losing on the spot! }
25... Rd1+ 26. Kg2 Qe6 27. Bf5 Qe1 { And white is getting mated. } *

