{ Removing the queen from the action. It is also more accurate than 12. Qb7 in the case that white wants to capture at a7. }
12... Rxc4 13. Qxa7 { The more complicated line for both players. } 13... Qc8
{ With the threat of trapping the queen. This maneuvere is only used to gain time to recover the pawn without worrying about the rook in the center of the board. Of course if white goes wrong, we accept the queen. }
14. Bg5 Qc6
{ Now it can be done because the bishop does not cover the b8-square, so the rook can go to b8. }
15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Rac1 Bxd4
{ Forcing white to be precise.   16...Ra8?!  is inaccurate:  17.Nxd5!  exd5?  18.Rxc4!  and white is suddenly winning!   After  17...Rxa7  18.Nxf6+  Nxf6  19.Bxc6  white is better. }
17. Qa3 { After this logical move we are much better. } 17... b5
{ Threatening the very obvious but still strong ...b5-b4, winning a piece. }
18. Qb3 Nc5
{ We are not trapping the queen, but we are heading to a winning queenless middlegame. }
19. Qxb5 Qxb5 20. Nxb5 Bxb2
{ With better pieces on the queenside. The a2-pawn is weak and the g2-bishop is out of play.  If white exchanges rooks on c4, the new c-pawn will be unstoppable. Otherwise, we will keep our active rook on c4 and bring the other rook to action. }
*

