[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 21: 4.g3 Main Line 9.Qa4 & 10.Rd1"]
[Black "13.Qf4 with 14.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3
{ The best move, and the one that is played the most by far. The bishop will be developed by g2, which allows a quick short castling. This solves white's problems with the king and early development. }
4... Bb7
{ Placing the bishop on the long diagonal at the first opportunity. The fight for the long diagonal is one of the most important in this position.It is important to notice that while the bishop on g2 will be defended with the king, the bishop on b7 most of the time will be unprotected. Therefore we need to be careful about anything happening on the long diagonal. }
5. Bg2
{ Other moves just end up transposing anyway. White wants to fight for the long diagonal as soon as possible and play O-O. }
5... Be7
{ Developing one more piece and allowing ...O-O. 5...d5 is not a good move since white is delaying Nc3. }
6. O-O
{ Swiftly hiding the king and protecting the g2-bishop. The rook can also be developed. }
6... O-O
{ Doing the same as white. White's knight is still at home so ...d5 is flawed. }
7. Nc3
{ The most logical move. White is developing the knight on its best square. e2-e4 and d4-d5 are looming. }
7... d5 { After Nc3 we can play ...d5 without any worries. } 8. Ne5
{ The main move. White is seeking the initiative, freeing the long diagonal for the g2-bishop. This move avoids the positions where black freed himself with ...dxc4. }
8... Nbd7
{ After Ne5 we will usually respond with ...Nbd7. This way we are ready to exchange the knight on e5 if we need to. }
9. Qa4
{ White threatens to play Nc6, winning the bishop pair and blocking the c-pawn. Black cannot allow this because black often depends on the ...c5 move to free himself. The d5-pawn would also be weak, as the b7-bishop would be exchanged. }
9... c6
{ The key move that maintains equality. In fact, black's position is easier to play. White has to be precise on many occasions. }
10. Rd1
{ The other main line of this position. It is an inaccuracy that leads to a very interesting position for black. }
10... Nxe5
{ On previous lines I said that we do not take on e5 if white can play dxe5 hitting the f6-knight. In the majority of cases it is true, but not here.In this case, the d5-pawn is well protected, bolstered with two pawns. Since there is no risk of losing the d5-pawn, we can play like this. }
11. dxe5 Nd7
{ Retreating the knight. Going forward would be a mistake for the same reasons as in the other lines with dxe5 and a knight on f6. But now we can go back and reroute the knight to a better place. We are also attacking the e5-pawn. }
12. cxd5 { The usual reply. Other moves are bad. } 12... exd5
{ This recapture leaves the e6-square for our pieces. The pawnchain d5-c6 is easier to mobilize than d5-e6.  We are going to expand on the queenside, and for that we need a pawn on the c-file.   After  12...cxd5  the b7-bishop is harder to activate and the e6-square is not available for our pieces. }
13. Qf4
{ Defending the e5-pawn, and removing the queen from a4 before it is hit with ...Nc5. }
13... Qc7 14. e4 d4 { The way is shut. } 15. Rxd4 Nxe5 16. Rd1 Rad8
{ We are better coordinated. } *

