1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 b6 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O Be7 6. d4 O-O 7. Re1 d5 8. cxd5
exd5 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Bf4 Ne4 11. Rc1 Nxc3 12. Rxc3 c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Rc2
{ In the course I check mainly  14.Rc1  because stockfish thinks it is better, but still the themes are the same. }
14... Nf6 15. Nd2 Re8
{ Black is just developing the pieces on sensible squares. } 16. Nc4 h6
{ Not needed. A move like 16...Qd7 defending the bishop looked more natural. }
17. Rd2 Qd7 18. Na5
{ Not taking advantatge of black's inaccuracy. The knight could be a liability on the edge of the board.   18.Be5  Rad8  19.e4⩲  Would put more pressure on black. White is forcing black to take decisions in the center. }
18... Ba6 19. a4 { Preventing ...Qb5 but missing black's idea. } 19... Qe6
{ Black is ready to take the center. After for instance ... Rad8 black can start mobilize his central pawns, taking a lot of space. The knight on a5 is odd. }
20. Rxd5
{ Overreacting. Black was better but there was no need to take such drastic measures.   20.Bxd5  More natural.  20...Nxd5  21.Rxd5  Rad8  22.e4  Bf6⩱  Black is slightly better and his position is easier to play but no major damage has been done. }
20... Qb6 21. Nc6 Nxd5
{ Taking the safe approach.   21...Qxc6!  It can be taken. It just requieres some fine calculation.  22.Rd6  Qxd6!  23.Bxd6  Rad8  24.Qc2  Bxd6-+  Black has a ton of material for the queen. }
22. Qxd5 Bf6
{ Black achieved an active position with extra material. It seems that the opening went well! This game shows how to play in the center in this kind of positions, freeing the center to inflict pain to white's position. In this case, an almost 2600 player just collapsed. }
