1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 b6 3. g3 Bb7 4. Bg2 e6 5. O-O Be7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Re1 d5 8. cxd5
exd5 9. d4 Nbd7 10. Bf4 Ne4 11. Qb3 Ndf6 12. Red1
{ Up until this move this game follows the course. On move 12 white has several rook moves to improve his position. Black's main ideas are mainly the same. }
12... c5
{ The main break. Black will have an IQP, but active minor pieces in the center. }
13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Be3 { Interesting rerouting of the bishop. }
15... Re8
{ Taking over the semi-open file, aiming at e2 and bolstering the e4-knight. }
16. Bd4 Ba6
{ Finding a better spot for the bishop. Trading it for the knight is also an idea. }
17. e3 Be2 18. Re1 Bxf3
{ The idea of this exchange is to take also on d4. Since there is no piece defending the bishop on d4 white must take with the pawn. That means that black has no longer a problem on d5 as white has the same 'weak' pawn. }
19. Bxf3 Bxd4 20. exd4
{ The knight on e4 is a good piece while white's light squared bishop is still not at full power. }
20... Qd6 { Connecting the rooks. } 21. Rac1 g6
{ Black gives some breathing space for his king. ...f5 could be an idea to bolstering the central knight. Later in the game Bologan made a mistake and lost, but it had nothing to do with the opening. }
