1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 b6 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O Be7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Re1 d5 8. d4
Nbd7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bf4 Ne4 11. Qb3 Ndf6 12. Rac1 c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. e3
{ In this case, white followed the main line of the course while black was the one who deviate. }
14... Qe7
{ A fine alternative. In this case black will not exchange on c3. This move mainly connect the rooks while placing the queen on a square where it cannot be disrupted. }
15. h3 { Preventing ...Ng4 attacking white's castle. } 15... Rac8 16. a3 Rfe8
{ Now both players are fully developed and the main action starts. } 17. Nb5 a6
18. Nc3 b5
{ Strange maneuver with the knight that allows black to expand on the queenside. }
19. Be5 Nd7 20. Bd4 Nb6
{ White has taken advantage of the last few moves to improve his dark squared bishop and has placed it on the same central square as Artemiev did on the previous game. Black meanwhile did the same with her knight to reinforce the queenside. }
21. Bxc5
{ Not a fan of this exchange by white but there is nothing wrong with it objectively. The c5-bishop was not doing that much and I think it does not deserve three move to exchange it. }
21... Nxc5 22. Qd1 Ne4 { Coming back to the best square. } 23. Qd4 Nc4
{ Activating the other knight. Usually black only has the e4-square for the knights but in this case black has found another good spot. }
24. Re2 { White made a mistake that was not punished. } 24... Ncd6
{ Returning the favor.   24...Nxb2!  25.Rxb2  or black is up a pawn for nothing  Rc4!  forcing  26.Qd3  Qxa3!  and the c3-knight is pinned in all directions  27.Rbc2  b4  and black is winning. }
25. Rec2 Nxc3 26. Rxc3 Rc4
{ Taking advantatge of the pawn structure that black had achieve earlier while white was wasting time. The game is around equal, but the c4 and e4-squares give black a lot of potential. Black ended up winning the game thanks to these squares along with a knight on d3 bolstered with a pawn on c4. }
