1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. b3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O b6 7. d4 Bb7 8. Bb2
dxc4 9. bxc4 c5 10. e3 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Rc8 12. Rc1 Rc7
{ This game follows the course until this move. In this case black wants to place the queen on a8 to pressure the center. }
13. a3
{ Already an inaccuracy.   13.Nh4=  White had to exchange the bishops right away to keep control of the center. }
13... Qa8 14. Nh4 Rd8 15. Qe2 Bxg2 16. Nxg2 Ne4
{ Black tries to occupy the center immediately but it has a flaw that could cost him the game.   16...Ne8  Black remains slightly better if he keeps his position together. There is no need to hurry. White cannot seize the center as the d4-pawn would be weak, and exchanging on d5 activates black's pieces while ruining white's pawn structure. For instance:  17.Rfd1  Bf6  18.h4  Nf8  19.Nf3  Qe4=  The game remains balanced. }
17. Nxe4 Qxe4 18. f3
{ Not getting advantage of black's misplay. The f3 move also weakens white's center since the push e3-e4 is not realistic.   18.d5±  Blocking the queen's escape route. According to engine white is better. }
18... Qb7
{ Black retreats and will attack the center with the bishop and rooks. Black is comfortably better. }
19. f4 { Also not great leaving a hole on e4. } 19... Qe4
{ Black is better and can strike in the center. The game still had some twists, but nothing to do with the opening. }
