1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. d5 exd5 8. Nh4
c6 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nf5 Nc7 11. Nc3 d5 12. e4 Bf6 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 cxd5
15. Ne3 Na6
{ Another path to reach the c5-square. It requires more precision than in the course recommendation. }
16. Nxd5 Nc5
{ 16...Bxd5??  With the knight on a6 it is not possible to take on d5 since the rook on a8 would be trapped by the two bishops.  17.Bxd5+- }
17. Rb1 Re8 18. Be3 Bxd5
{ This move allows white to keep some pressure with the bishop pair. But now black is less constrained and can fully develop at last. }
19. Bxd5 Rc8 20. Qf3 Qe7 21. Rfd1 Rcd8
{ Black pieces are on their best squares and although the engine gives white an edge, it is not easy to suggest an improvement for white. }
22. b3 Na6 23. Bd4 Nb4 24. Bxf6 Qxf6 25. Qxf6 gxf6
{ Black's structure is worst but actually this wrecked kingside structure is good for defensive purpose since it is very difficult to advance white's pawns without improving black's kingside @@StartBracket@@g5 for white will most likely be answered with ...fxg5@@EndBracket@@. Black can easily achieve a draw in this kind of positions even if you are playing against a stronger opponent like in the current game. }
