1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. d5 exd5 8. Nh4
c6 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nf5 Nc7 11. e4 d5 12. Re1 Bf6
{ There are a lot of top-level games with this kind of games with 7. d5! } 13.
Nc3 Bc8
{ A typical maneuver in this position. The b7-bishop is doing nothing as it is severly blocked. So if black can afford to get it back to play, he must consider it. }
14. Qf3 Re8 { Reaching the course.. } 15. Bd2
{ I guess the goal of this move was to connect the rooks, but it is not correct.   15.Rd1  , stopping the d-pawn, was better. }
15... Nd7
{ A good move but there was a better alternative. This move requires more precision for the black player.   15...d4!  Would have left white on the brink with an easier path to walk for black.  16.Ne2  c5∓  The engine prefers 16...Nd7, but this move is simpler and shows that black is just a pawn up with a protected passed pawn on d4. After ...Nd7-Ne5 and finding a place for the light sqaured bishop, black will be clearly better. }
16. exd5 Ne5 17. Qh5 g6 18. Nh6+ Kg7 19. Qd1 cxd5
{ This move levels the game again.   19...Nxd5!  Apparently only this move gives an edge  20.Nxd5  cxd5  It makes sense that removing an enemy attacker and our defender is better for us since the rest remains equal as in the game.  21.h4  Bb7⩱  Black is a pawn up and it is not clear at all that white can take it back in the near future. About the knight on h6, I am not entirely sure if this piece is attacking, trapped or both! }
20. Bf4 Bb7 21. Bxe5
{ Returning the favor.   21.Rc1=  Just playing with all pieces on the board is better since black is lacking some breathing space. }
21... Rxe5 { Exchanging even more pieces. } 22. Rxe5 Bxe5 23. Ng4
{ I guess retreating this knight was the idea behind these exchanges, but now black is fine. }
23... Qd6 { Black just consolidated his extra pawn and went on to win. } 24.
Qd2 h5 25. Nxe5 Qxe5 26. Re1 Qf6 27. Rd1 Re8 28. h4 Qe5 29. a3 Rd8 30. Re1 Qf6
