1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 d5 8. Ne5
Nbd7 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Bf4 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Qd7 13. Rc1 Rac8
{ Matching the course. } 14. h4
{ In some cases, the bishop on e5 could be trapped with ...f6-g5. 14. h4 makes ...g7-g5 virtually impossible. }
14... c5 15. Kh2 Rcd8
{ ...c4 followed with an expansion on the queenside is the main thread. } 16.
b3 Rfe8 17. Qc2 Bf8
{ The bishop is not doing anything and is not easy to improve it for now. Therefore we remove it from the e7-square where it blocks the rook, waiting for the right moment to reactivate it. It also allows black to play along the e-file. }
18. Rfd1 Qe7
{ Nice move! It looked like black was only shifting his pieces back and forth but it had a purpose. Black is increasing the pressure on the e file, aiming at the e2-pawn and the e4-square. }
19. Bf3 b5
{ Black starts mobilizing his queenside. The e5-bishop is only protected with the d4-pawn, so white cannot take on c5. With the queen on the d-file white could respond with e4, followed with dxc5 menacing the black queen. }
20. Bf4 { White removes the bishop from his dangerous spot. } 20... c4
{ The main idea. } 21. bxc4 bxc4
{ Black has achieved his objective: an advantage on the queenside with a protected passed pawn. }
22. Qa4 Qa3 23. Qxa3 Bxa3 24. Rb1 Bc6 25. Bd2
{ The mistake. White removes the defender of the b8-square. Now black can fight for the open file which will help the advance of the c-pawn with moves like ...Rb2 and ...Bb2. Black finished it off with a great technique. }
25... Rb8 26. Bc3 Rb6 27. Ba5 Rb2 28. Rxb2 Bxb2 29. Rb1 Bxd4 30. e3 Bf6 31. Rd1
