Bb7 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Bg5
{ Reaching the same position of the course a move later due to black's maneuver of ...Bb4+ and ...Be7. }
10... h6 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. cxd5 exd5
{ With the same position as in the course. } 14. e3
{ White has a healthy structure and well placed pieces, although it is not easy to suggest moves that improves his position. }
14... Rfd8
{ On the other hand, black has the bishop pair and a pawn structure that is easier to mobilize with ...c7-c5. }
15. Qh5 a5 { Expanding on the queenside, trying to force weaknesses. } 16. Rfd1
a4 17. a3 Ra5 18. Rac1 c6
{ Since the c5-break is still not possible, black is bolstering the d5-pawn, so he can improve his light squared bishop to a6 or c8.   18...c5?!  In this position is inaccurate. I show this line to see the difference with the game.  19.dxc5  Rxc5  Black's idea.  20.Nxd5!  This move is a killer. In the game this move is not possible.  20...Rxc1  21.Nxf6+⩲ }
19. Rd2 { This move allows ...c5. } 19... c5 20. Ne2
{ This allows black's further expansion on the queenside.   20.dxc5  Now the line that was bothering us is no longer better for white.  20...Rxc5  21.Nxd5??   21.Qd1=  Is the best move, reinforcing white's position and keeping the balance intact.  Rxc1+-+  Because now this capture is a check! }
20... c4 21. Nc3 { Not sure what white is doing with this knight... } 21... Be7
{ Black has achieved the kind of position we want. The grip on the queenside @@StartBracket@@...b5-b4@@EndBracket@@ made the white player crack. }
