1. d4
{ Last but not least I show one of my own games where I faced a higher rated player and I managed to beat him very convincingly. }
1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. Ne5 O-O 8. Nc3
Nbd7 9. Qa4 c6 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 11. Qxc6 Rc8 12. Qb5 Rxc4 13. e3 Bb4 14. a3
{ A natural move, attacking the b4-bishop. But this is a mistake and white is already worse.   As shown in the course, in this position white needs to sacrifice on  d5  to get a game. In the course, I gave both  14.Nxd5  and  14.Bxd5  for white. }
14... Bxc3
{ The usual response, even if white does not play a3. So black has just won one tempo. }
15. bxc3 Qc7
{ 15...Rxc3?!  Not bad but the main goal of black is to keep the bishops closed, and this move gives some hope to the c1-bishop. Black is a pawn up, but it is not needed since the c3-pawn is a permanent weakness that white has to worry about.  16.Bb2  Rc2  17.Rfc1  a6  18.Qb3  Rxc1+  19.Rxc1  Qa8⩱   15...Qc8!  Securing the a6-square for the pawn is more precise.  16.a4  a6∓ }
16. Bd2 Ne4
{ Baiting white to exchange his 'good' bishop for the knight. The knight on e4 is attacking the d2-bishop and the c3-pawn, so white needs to do something. }
17. Bxe4
{ Sad necessity, but now white has only the bad bishop and just a worse position.   17.Rfd1?!  Nxd2  18.Rxd2  Rxc3-+  This way black takes the pawn on c3 in a better way. White cannot contest the c-file and black's knight is still a better piece than the remaining bishop. }
17... dxe4 18. a4 a5 { Removing all chances of counter attacking. } 19. f3 Nf6
20. Rab1 Rb8
{ Black's position is better, with the knight dominating the bishop. The job is not done yet, but it no longer has nothing to do with the opening. }
